\id JHN Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h John
\mt1 The Holy Gospel of Jesus Christ according to John.
\c 1
\p
\v 0 Then, the testimonies of John Baptist, first to the solemn \add legacy of the Jews: 29. secondly, when he saw \sc Jesus\sc* come to him: 35. thirdly, to his own Disciples also, putting them over from himself to \sc Jesus\sc*. Who made it plainer to them that he is Christ, 40. and so began he also to have Disciples.\add* \f + \fr 1:0 \ft The 1. part: THE ACTS of Christ before his manifestation, whilst John Baptist was yet baptizing.\f*
\v 1 In the beginning was the \sc Word\sc*, and the \sc Word\sc* was with God, and God was the \sc Word\sc*. \f + \fr 1:1 \ft The Gospel at the third Mass upon Christmas day. And every day at the end of Mass.\f*
\v 2 This was in the beginning with God.
\v 3 All things were made by him: and without him was made nothing. That which was made, \f + \fr 1:3 \ft nothing that was made.\f*
\v 4 in him was life, and the life was the light of men:
\v 5 and the light shineth in darkness, and the darkness did not comprehend it.
\v 6 There was a man sent from God, whose name was John.
\v 7 This man came for testimony; to give testimony of the light, that all might believe through him.
\v 8 He was not the light, but to give testimony of the light.
\v 9 It was the true light, which lighteneth every man that cometh into this world.
\v 10 He was in the world, and the world was made by him, and the world knew him not.
\v 11 He came into his own, and his own received him not.
\v 12 But as many as received him, he gave them power to be made the sons of God, to those that believe in his name.
\v 13 Who, not of blood, nor of the will of flesh, nor of the will of man, but of God are born.
\v 14 \sc And The Word Was Made Flesh\sc*, and dwelt in us (and we saw the glory of him, glory as it were of the Only-begotten of the Father) full of grace and verity. \f + \fr 1:14 \ft ET VERBUM CARO FACTUM EST.\f*
\v 15 John giveth testimony of him, and cryeth saying: This was he of whom I spake, He that shall come after me, is made before me: because he was before me.
\v 16 And of his fullness we all have received, and grace for grace. \f + \fr 1:16 \ft He is preferred & made of more dignity and excellency than I, because he was before me & all things, eternal God.\f*
\v 17 For the law was given by Moyses, grace and verity was made by \sc Jesus\sc* Christ.
\v 18 God no man hath seen at any time: the only-begotten Son which is in the bosom of the Father, he hath declared.
\v 19 And this is John's testimony, when the Jews sent from Jerusalem Priests and Levites to him, that they should ask him, who art thou? \f + \fr 1:19 \ft The Gospel upon the 3. Sunday in Advent.\f*
\v 20 And he confessed, and did not deny: and he confessed, That I am not \sc Christ\sc*.
\v 21 And they asked him: What then? Art thou Elias? And he said: I am not. Art thou the Prophet? And he answered: No. \f + \fr 1:21 \ft By like the Jews ignorantly understood not the place in Deuteronomy, of Christ, and therefore they ask also whether he be the Prophet there spoken of. See also c. 7, 40.\f*
\v 22 They said therefore unto him: Who art thou, that we may give an answer to them that sent us? what sayest thou of thyself?
\v 23 He said: \add I am the voice of one crying in the desert, make straight the way of our Lord,\add* as Esaie the Prophet said.
\v 24 And they that were sent were of the Pharisees.
\v 25 And they asked him, and said to him: Why then doest thou baptize, if thou be not Christ, nor Elias, nor the Prophet?
\v 26 John answered them, saying: I baptize in water; but there hath stood in the midst of you whom you know not. \f + \fr 1:26 \ft He doth often here signify the great difference of his Baptism & of Christ's, as of his person & Christ's. See Annot. Mat. 3.\f*
\v 27 The same is he that shall come after me, that is made before me; whose latchet of his shoe I am not worthy to loose.
\v 28 These things were done in Bethania beyond Jordan, where John was baptizing.
\v 29 The next day John saw \sc Jesus\sc* coming to him, and he saith: \add Behold the lamb of God, behold him that taketh away the \add* \add sin of the world.\add* \f + \fr 1:29 \ft The Gospel on the octave of the Epiphany.\f* \f + \fr 1:29 \ft sins\f* \f + \fr 1:29 \ft AGNUS DEI at Mass.\f*
\v 30 This is he of whom I said: After me there cometh a man, which is made before me: because he was before me.
\v 31 And I knew him not, but that he may be manifested in Israel, therefore came I baptizing in water.
\v 32 And John gave testimony, saying: That I saw the Spirit descending as a dove from Heaven, and he remained upon him.
\v 33 And I knew him not: but he that sent me to baptize in water, he said to me: He upon whom thou shalt see the Spirit descending and remaining upon him, he it is that baptizeth in the Holy Ghost.
\v 34 And I saw; and I gave testimony that this is the Son of God.
\v 35 The next day again John stood, and two of his Disciples. \f + \fr 1:35 \ft The Gospel upon S. Andrew's eve.\f*
\v 36 And beholding \sc Jesus\sc* walking, he saith: Behold the Lamb of God.
\v 37 And the two Disciples heard him speaking, and they followed \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 38 And \sc Jesus\sc* turning, and seeing them following him, saith to them, What seek you? Who said to him: Rabbi (which is called by interpretation, Master) where dwellest thou?
\v 39 He saith to them: Come and see. They came, and saw where he abode, and they tarried with him that day: and it was about the tenth hour.
\v 40 And Andrew the brother of Simon Peter was one of the two that had heard of John, and followed him.
\v 41 He findeth first his brother Simon, and saith to him: We have found \sc Messias\sc*, which is being interpreted, \sc Christ\sc*. \f + \fr 1:41 \ft Messias in Hebrew, in Greek Christ, in English Anointed, to wit, with the spiritual oil of grace above his brethren. Ps. 44.\f*
\v 42 And he brought him to \sc Jesus\sc*. And \sc Jesus\sc* looking upon him, said: Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called \add Cephas,\add* which is interpreted, Peter. \f + \fr 1:42 \ft Cephas in Syriac, & Peter in Greek, in English, Rock. See Mat. 16, 18.\f*
\v 43 On the morrow he would go forth into Galilee, and he findeth Philippe. And \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: Follow me.
\v 44 And Philippe was of Bethsaida, the city of Andrew and Peter.
\v 45 Philippe findeth Nathanael, and saith to him: Him whom Moyses in the law, and the Prophets wrote of, we have found, \sc Jesus\sc* the son of Joseph, of Nazareth.
\v 46 And Nathanael said to him: From Nazareth can there be any good? Philippe saith to him: Come and see.
\v 47 \sc Jesus\sc* saw Nathanael coming to him, and he saith of him: Behold an Israelite in very deed, in whom there is no guile. \f + \fr 1:47 \ft The Gospel in a votive Mass of the holy Angels.\f*
\v 48 Nathanael saith to him: How knowest thou me? \sc Jesus\sc* answered and said to him: Before that Philippe did call thee, when thou wast under the figtree, I saw thee.
\v 49 Nathanael answered him and saith: Rabbi, thou art the Son of God, thou art the King of Israel.
\v 50 \sc Jesus\sc* answered, and said to him: Because I said unto thee, I saw thee under the figtree, thou believest; greater than these things shalt thou see.
\v 51 And he saith to him: Amen Amen I say to you, You shall see the Heaven opened, and the Angels of God ascending and descending, upon the Son of man. \f + \fr 1:51 \ft Peter by his new\f*
\c 2
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* the third day there was a marriage made in Cana of Galilee: and the mother of \sc Jesus\sc* was there. \f + \fr 2:1 \ft The Gospel upon the 2. Sunday after the Epiphany.\f*
\v 2 And \sc Jesus\sc* also was called, and his Disciples to the marriage.
\v 3 And the wine failing, the mother of \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: They have no wine.
\v 4 And \sc Jesus\sc* saith to her: What is to me and thee woman? My hour cometh not yet.
\v 5 His mother saith to the ministers: Whatsoever he shall say to you, do ye.
\v 6 And there were set there six water-pots of stone, according to the purification of the Jews, holding every one two or three measures.
\v 7 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: Fill the water-pots with water. And they filled them up to the top.
\v 8 And \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: Draw now, and carry to the chief steward. And they carried it.
\v 9 And after the chief steward tasted the water made wine, and knew not whence it was, but the ministers knew that had drawn the water; the chief steward calleth the bridegroom, \f + \fr 2:9 \ft He that seeth water turned in to wine, needeth not dispute or doubt how Christ changed bread into his body.\f*
\v 10 and saith to him: Every man first setteth the good wine, and when they have well drunk, then that which is worse. But thou hast kept the good wine until now.
\v 11 This beginning of miracles did \sc Jesus\sc* in Cana of Galilee: and he manifested his glory, and his Disciples believed in him.
\v 12 After this he went down to Capharnaum himself and his mother, and his brethren, and his Disciples; and there they remained not many days.
\v 13 And the Pasch of the Jews was at hand, and \sc Jesus\sc* went up to Jerusalem: \f + \fr 2:13 \ft The Gospel upon Monday in the fourth week of Lent.\f*
\v 14 and he found in the Temple them that sold oxen and sheep and doves, and the bankers sitting.
\v 15 And when he had made as it were a whip of little cords, he cast them all out of the temple, the sheep also and the oxen, and the money of the bankers he poured out, and the tables he overthrew.
\v 16 And to them that sold doves, he said: Take away these things hence, and make not the house of my Father, a house of merchandise.
\v 17 And his Disciples remembered that it is written: \add The zeal of thy house hath eaten me.\add*
\v 18 The Jews therefore answered and said to him: What sign doest thou shew us, that thou doest these things?
\v 19 \sc Jesus\sc* answered and said to them: Dissolve this temple, and in three days I will raise it.
\v 20 The Jews therefore said: In forty and six years was this temple built, & wilt thou raise it in three days?
\v 21 But he spake of the temple of his body.
\v 22 Therefore when he was risen again from the dead, his Disciples remembered, that he said this, and they believed the scripture and the word that \sc Jesus\sc* did say.
\v 23 And when he was at Jerusalem in the Pasch, upon the festival day, many believed in his name, seeing his signs which he did.
\v 24 But \sc Jesus\sc* did not commit himself unto them, for that he knew all,
\v 25 and because it was not needful for him that any should give testimony of man; for he knew what was in man.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* there was a man of the Pharisees, named Nicodemus, a Prince of the Jews. \f + \fr 3:1 \ft The Gospel upon Holy Rood day, or Invention of the holy Cross. Maij 3.\f*
\v 2 This man came to \sc Jesus\sc* by night, and said to him: Rabbi, we know that thou art come from God a Master; for no man can do these signs which thou doest, unless God be with him.
\v 3 \sc Jesus\sc* answered, and said to him: Amen, Amen I say to thee, unless a man be born again, he cannot see the Kingdom of God.
\v 4 Nicodemus said to him: How can a man be born, when he is old? can he enter into his mother's womb again & be born?
\v 5 \sc Jesus\sc* answered: Amen, Amen I say to thee, unless a man be born again of water and the Spirit, he cannot enter into the Kingdom of God.
\v 6 That which is born of the flesh, is flesh: & that which is born of the Spirit, is spirit.
\v 7 Marvel not, that I said to thee, You must be born again.
\v 8 The Spirit breatheth where he will; and thou hearest his voice, but thou knowest not whence he cometh and whither he goeth: so is every one that is born of the Spirit. \f + \fr 3:8 \ft We follow rather S. August. & those ancient Fathers, which most commonly understand this place of the Holy Ghost, & not of the wind: although both senses be good.\f*
\v 9 Nicodemus answered, & said to him: How can these things be done?
\v 10 \sc Jesus\sc* answered, and said to him: Thou art a Master in Israel, and art thou ignorant of these things?
\v 11 Amen, Amen I say to thee, that we speak that which we know, and that which we have seen we testify, and our testimony you receive not.
\v 12 If I have spoken to you earthly things, and you believe not: how if I shall speak to you heavenly things, will you believe?
\v 13 And no man hath ascended into Heaven, but he that descended from Heaven, the Son of man which is in Heaven.
\v 14 And as Moyses exalted the serpent in the desert, so must the Son of man be exalted:
\v 15 that every one which believeth in him, perish not, but may have life everlasting.
\v 16 For so God loved the world, that he gave his only-begotten Son; that every one that believeth in him, perish not, but may have life everlasting. \f + \fr 3:16 \ft The Gospel upon Monday in the Whitsunweek.\f*
\v 17 For God sent not his Son into the world, to judge the world, but that the world may be saved by him.
\v 18 He that believeth in him, is not judged. But he that doth not believe, is already judged: because he hath not believed in the name of the only-begotten Son of God.
\v 19 And this is the judgement: because the light is come into the world, and men have loved the darkness rather than the light: for their works were evil.
\v 20 For every one that doeth ill, hateth the light, and cometh not to the light, that his works may not be controlled.
\v 21 But he that doeth verity, cometh to the light, that his works may be made manifest, because they were done in God.
\v 22 After these things \sc Jesus\sc* came and his Disciples into the country of Jewry; & there he abode with them, and baptized.
\v 23 And John also was baptizing in Ænon beside Salim; because there was much water there, and they came, and were baptized.
\v 24 For John was not yet cast into prison.
\v 25 And there rose a question of John's Disciples with the Jews concerning purification.
\v 26 And they came to John, and said to him: Rabbi, he that was with thee beyond Jordan, to whom thou didst give testimony, behold he baptizeth, and all come to him.
\v 27 John answered and said: A man cannot receive any thing, unless it be given him from Heaven,
\v 28 Yourselves do bear me witness, that I said, I am not \sc Christ\sc*; but that I am sent before him.
\v 29 He that hath the bride, is the bridegroom: but the friend of the bridegroom that standeth and heareth him, rejoiceth with joy for the voice of the bridegroom. This my joy therefore is filled.
\v 30 He must increase, and I diminish.
\v 31 He that cometh from above, is above all. He that is of the earth, of the earth he is, and of the earth he speaketh. He that cometh from Heaven, is above all.
\v 32 And what he hath seen and heard, that he testifieth: and his testimony no man receiveth.
\v 33 He that hath received his testimony, hath signed that God is true.
\v 34 For he whom God hath sent, speaketh the words of God. For God doth not give the Spirit by measure.
\v 35 The Father loveth the Son: & he hath given all things in his hand.
\v 36 He that believeth in the Son: hath life everlasting: but he that is incredulous to the Son, shall not see life, but the wrath of God remaineth upon him.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 \sc When Jesus\sc* therefore understood that the Pharisees heard that \sc Jesus\sc* maketh more Disciples, and baptizeth, than John,
\v 2 (howbeit \sc Jesus\sc* did not baptize, but his Disciples) \f + \fr 4:2 \ft He did not baptize ordinarily: yet that he baptized his Apostles, S. Aug. thinketh it very probable, ep. 108.\f*
\v 3 he left Jewry, and went again into Galilee.
\v 4 And he had of necessity to pass through Samaria.
\v 5 He cometh therefore into a city of Samaria which is called Sichar; beside the manor that Jacob gave to Joseph his son. \f + \fr 4:5 \ft The Gospel upon Friday in the 3. week in Lent.\f*
\v 6 And there was there the fountain of Jacob. \sc Jesus\sc* therefore wearied of his journey, sat so upon the fountain. It was about the sixth hour.
\v 7 There cometh a woman of Samaria to draw water. \sc Jesus\sc* said to her: Give me to drink. \f + \fr 4:7 \ft This woman is a figure of the Church, not yet justified, but now to be justified. Aug. tract. 15 in Ioan.\f*
\v 8 For his Disciples were gone into the city, to buy meats.
\v 9 Therefore that Samaritane woman saith to him: How doest thou being a Jew, ask of me to drink, which am a Samaritane woman? For the Jews do not communicate with the Samaritans. \f + \fr 4:9 \ft There were many other causes why the faithful Jews could not abide the Samaritans, but their precise abstaining from their company & conversation, was their Schismatical Temple and service in mount Garizim.\f*
\v 10 \sc Jesus\sc* answered, and said to her: If thou didst know the gift of God, and who he is that saith unto thee, Give me to drink; thou perhaps wouldest have asked of him, and he would have given thee living water.
\v 11 The woman saith to him: Sir, neither hast thou wherein to draw, and the well is deep; whence hast thou the living water?
\v 12 art thou greater than our Father Jacob, who gave us the well, & himself drank of it, and his children, and his cattle?
\v 13 \sc Jesus\sc* answered, and said to her: Every one that drinketh of this water, shall thirst again; but he that shall drink of the water that I will give him, shall not thirst for ever, \f + \fr 4:13 \ft c He speaketh of his baptizing in the Holy Ghost. See Io. c. 7, 39.\f*
\v 14 but the water that I will give him, shall become in him a fountain of water springing up unto life everlasting.
\v 15 The woman saith to him: Lord give me this water, that I may not thirst, nor come hither to draw.
\v 16 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to her: Go, call thy husband, and come hither.
\v 17 The woman answered and said: I have no husband. \sc Jesus\sc* said to her: Thou hast said well, that I have no husband.
\v 18 For thou hast had five husbands; and he whom thou now hast, is not thy husband. This thou hast said truly.
\v 19 The woman saith to him: Lord, I perceive that thou art a Prophet.
\v 20 Our Fathers adored in this mountain, and you say, that at Jerusalem is the place where men must adore.
\v 21 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to her: Woman believe me, that the hour shall come, when you shall neither in this mountain, nor in Jerusalem adore the Father.
\v 22 You adore that you know not: we adore that we know; for salvation is of the Jews.
\v 23 But the hour cometh, and now it is, when the true adorers shall adore the Father in spirit and verity. For the Father also seeketh such to adore him.
\v 24 God is a Spirit, and they that adore him, must adore in spirit and verity.
\v 25 The woman saith to him: I know that \sc Messias\sc* cometh, (which is called \sc Christ\sc*) therefore when he cometh, he will shew us all things.
\v 26 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to her: I am he, that speak with thee.
\v 27 And incontinent his Disciples came: and they marveled that he talked with a woman. No man for all that said: What seekest thou, or why talkest thou with her?
\v 28 The woman therefore left her water-pot: and she went into the city, and saith to those men:
\v 29 Come, and see a man that hath told me all things whatsoever I have done. Is not he \sc Christ\sc*?
\v 30 They went forth therefore out of the city, and came to him.
\v 31 In the mean time the Disciples desired him, saying: Rabbi eat.
\v 32 But he said to them: I have meat to eat which you know not.
\v 33 The Disciples therefore said one to another: Hath any man brought him for to eat?
\v 34 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: My meat is to do the will of him that sent me, to perfit his work.
\v 35 Do not you say that yet there are four months, and harvest cometh? Behold I say to you, lift up your eyes, and see the Countries, that they are white already to harvest.
\v 36 And he that reapeth, receiveth hire, and gathereth fruit unto life everlasting: that both he that soweth, and he that reapeth, may rejoice together.
\v 37 For in this is the saying true: that it is one man that soweth, and it is another that reapeth.
\v 38 I have sent you to reap that which you laboured not: others have laboured, & you have entered into their labours.
\v 39 And of that city many believed in him of the Samaritans, for the word of the woman giving testimony, that he told me all things whatsoever I have done. \f + \fr 4:39 \ft This woman mystically being the Church, it is here signified, that they which at the first believe because the Church teacheth so, afterward be much confirmed, finding it in the Scripture also, and by other instructions.\f*
\v 40 Therefore when the Samaritans were come to him, they desired him that he would tarry there. And he tarried there two days.
\v 41 And many more believed for his own word.
\v 42 And they said to the woman, That now not for thy saying do we believe; for ourselves have heard, and do know that this is the Saviour of the world indeed.
\v 43 And after two days he departed thence; and went into Galilee.
\v 44 For \sc Jesus\sc* himself gave testimony that a Prophet hath not honour in his own country:
\v 45 Therefore when he was come into Galilee, the Galilæans received him, whereas they had seen all things that he had done at Jerusalem in the festival day: for themselves also came to the festival day.
\v 46 He came again therefore into Cana of Galilee, where he made water wine. And there was a certain lord whose son was sick at Capharnaum. \f + \fr 4:46 \ft The Gospel upon the 20. Sunday after Pentecost.\f*
\v 47 He having heard that \sc Jesus\sc* came from Jewry into Galilee, went to him, and desired him that he would come down and heal his son, For he began to die.
\v 48 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said to him: Unless you see signs and wonders, you believe not.
\v 49 The lord saith to him: Lord, come down before that my son die.
\v 50 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: Go, thy son liveth. The man believed the word that \sc Jesus\sc* said to him, and went.
\v 51 And as he was now going down, his servants met him: and they brought word, saying, That his son lived.
\v 52 He asked therefore of them the hour, wherein he was amended. And they said to him, That yesterday at the seventh hour the fever left him.
\v 53 The father therefore knew that it was in the same hour wherein \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Thy son liveth, and himself believed and his whole house.
\v 54 This again the second sign did \sc Jesus\sc*, when he was come from Jewry into Galilee.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 \sc After\sc* these things there was a festival day of the Jews, and \sc Jesus\sc* went up to Jerusalem. \f + \fr 5:1 \ft The Gospel upon Imber Friday in the first week of Lent.\f*
\v 2 And there is at Jerusalem upon Probatica a pond which in Hebrew is surnamed Bethsaida, having five porches. \f + \fr 5:2 \ft By our Latin text and the Greek, this miraculous pond was in or upon Probatica, that is, a place where the sheep to be sacrificed, were kept. But by other Latin copies, S. Hierom, and some Greek Fathers, Probatica is the very pond itself: so called, because the sheep of sacrifice were there washed.\f* \f + \fr 5:2 \ft Bethesda,\f*
\v 3 In these lay a great multitude of sick persons, of blind, lame, withered, expecting the stirring of the water.
\v 4 And an Angel of our Lord descended at a certain time into the pond; and the water was stirred. And he that had gone down first into the pond after the stirring of the water, was made whole of whatsoever infirmity he was holden.
\v 5 And there was a certain man there that had been eight and thirty years in his infirmity.
\v 6 Him when \sc Jesus\sc* had seen lying, & knew that he had now a long time, he saith to him: Wilt thou be made whole? \f + \fr 5:6 \ft c multum tempus haberet,\f*
\v 7 The sick man answered him: Lord, I have no man, when the water is troubled, to put me into the pond. For whiles I come, another goeth down before me.
\v 8 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: Arise, take up thy bed, and walk.
\v 9 And forthwith he was made whole: and he took up his bed, and walked. And it was the Sabboth that day.
\v 10 The Jews therefore said to him that was healed: It is the Sabboth, thou mayst not take up thy bed.
\v 11 He answered them: He that made me whole, he said to me, take up thy bed, and walk.
\v 12 They asked him therefore, what is that man that said to thee, take up thy bed, and walk?
\v 13 But he that was made whole, knew not who it was. For \sc Jesus\sc* shrunk aside from the multitude standing in the place.
\v 14 Afterward \sc Jesus\sc* findeth him in the temple, & said to him: Behold thou art made whole; sin no more, lest some worse thing chance to thee.
\v 15 That man went his way, and told the Jews that it was \sc Jesus\sc* that made him whole.
\v 16 Thereupon the Jews persecuted \sc Jesus\sc*, because he did these things on the Sabboth.
\v 17 But \sc Jesus\sc* answered them: My Father worketh until now; and I do work.
\v 18 Thereupon therefore the Jews sought the more to kill him: because he did not only break the Sabboth, but also he said God was his Father, making himself equal to God.
\v 19 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore answered, and said to them: Amen, amen, I say to you, the Son cannot do any thing of himself, but that which he seeth the Father doing. For what things soever he doeth, these the Son also doeth in like manner.
\v 20 For the Father loveth the Son, and sheweth him all things that himself doeth, and greater works than these will he shew him, that you may marvel.
\v 21 For as the Father doth raise the dead and quickeneth: so the Son also quickeneth whom he will.
\v 22 For neither doth the Father judge any man: but all judgement he hath given to the Son,
\v 23 that all may honour the Son, as they do honour the Father. He that honoureth not the Son, doth not honour the Father, who sent him.
\v 24 Amen, amen I say to you, that he which heareth my word, and believeth him that sent me, hath life everlasting: and he cometh not into judgement, but shall pass from death into life. \f + \fr 5:24 \ft is passed.\f*
\v 25 Amen, amen I say to you, that the hour cometh, and now it is when the dead shall hear the voice of the Son of God, and they that have heard, shall live. \f + \fr 5:25 \ft The Gospel upon All souls day.\f*
\v 26 For as the Father hath life in himself; so he hath given to the Son also to have life in himself:
\v 27 and he hath given him power to do judgement also because he is the Son of man.
\v 28 Marvel not at this, because the hour cometh wherein all that are in the graves, shall hear his voice,
\v 29 and they that have done good things, shall come forth into the resurrection of life: but they that have done evil into the resurrection of judgement. \f + \fr 5:29 \ft Not faith only, but good and ill deeds shall be counted, and accordingly rewarded at the day of judgement.\f*
\v 30 I cannot of myself do any thing. As I hear, so I judge: and my judgement is just, because I seek not my will, but the will of him that sent me.
\v 31 If I give testimony of myself, my testimony is not true.
\v 32 There is another that giveth testimony of me: and I know that the testimony is true which he giveth of me.
\v 33 You sent to John; and he gave testimony to the truth,
\v 34 But I receive not testimony of man: but I say these things that you may be saved.
\v 35 He was the lamp burning and shining. And you would for a time rejoice in his light.
\v 36 But I have a greater testimony than John. For the works which the Father hath given me to perfit them: the very works themselves which I do, give testimony of me, that the Father hath sent me.
\v 37 And the Father that sent me, himself hath given testimony of me: neither have you heard his voice at any time, nor seen his shape,
\v 38 and his word you have not remaining in you: because whom he hath sent, him you believe not.
\v 39 Search the scriptures, for you think in them to have life everlasting: & the same are they that give testimony of me: \f + \fr 5:39 \ft Catholics search the scriptures, and find there, Peter's & his successors Primacy, the real presence, the Priest's power to forgive sins, justification by faith & good works, Virginity preferred before matrimony, breach of the vow of continency damnable, voluntary poverty, Penance, alms,\f*
\v 40 and you will not come to me that you may have life.
\v 41 Glory of men I receive not.
\v 42 But I have known you, that the love of God you have not in you.
\v 43 I am come in the name of my Father, and you receive me not: if another shall come in his own name, him you will receive. \f + \fr 5:43 \ft He meaneth specially Antichrist. How then can the\f*
\v 44 How can you believe, that receive glory one of another: and the glory which is of God only, you seek not?
\v 45 Think not that I will accuse you to the Father. There is that accuseth you, Moyses, in whom you trust.
\v 46 For if you did believe Moyses: you would perhaps believe me also. For of me he hath written.
\v 47 And if you do not believe his writings: how will you believe my words.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 \sc After\sc* these things \sc Jesus\sc* went beyond the sea of Galilee, which is of Tiberias. \f + \fr 6:1 \ft The Gospel upon Mid-lent Sunday.\f*
\v 2 and a great multitude followed him, because they saw the signs which he did upon those that were sick.
\v 3 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore went up into the mountain, and there he sat with his Disciples.
\v 4 And the Pasch was at hand, the festival day of the Jews.
\v 5 When \sc Jesus\sc* therefore had lifted up his eyes, and saw that a very great multitude cometh to him, he saith to Philippe: Whence shall we buy bread, that these may eat?
\v 6 And this he said, tempting him. For himself knew what he would do?
\v 7 Philippe answered him: Two hundred penny worth of bread is not sufficient for them, that every man may take a little piece.
\v 8 One of his Disciples, Andrew the brother of Simon Peter, saith to him:
\v 9 There is a boy here that hath five barley loaves, & two fishes; but what are these among so many?
\v 10 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore saith: Make the men to sit down. And there was much grass in the place. The men therefore sat down, in number about five thousand.
\v 11 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore took the loaves; and when he had given thanks, he distributed to them that sat. In like manner also of the fishes as much as they would.
\v 12 And after they were filled, he said to his Disciples: Gather the fragments that are remaining, lest they be lost.
\v 13 They gathered therefore, and filled twelve baskets with fragments of the five barley loaves, which remained to them that had eaten.
\v 14 Those men therefore when they had seen what a sign \sc Jesus\sc* had done, said, That this is the Prophet indeed that is to come into the world.
\v 15 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore when he knew that they would come to take him, and make him king, he fled again into the mountain himself alone.
\v 16 And when even was come, his Disciples went down to the sea.
\v 17 And when they were gone up into the ship, they came beyond the sea into Capharnaum: And now it was dark and \sc Jesus\sc* was not come unto them.
\v 18 And the sea arose, by reason of a great wind that blew.
\v 19 When they had rowed therefore about five and twenty or thirty furlongs, they see \sc Jesus\sc* walking upon the sea, and to draw nigh to the ship, and they feared.
\v 20 But he said to them: It is I, fear not.
\v 21 They would therefore have taken him into the ship: and forthwith the ship was at the land to which they went.
\v 22 The next day, the multitude that stood beyond the sea, saw that there was no other boat there but one, and that \sc Jesus\sc* had not entered into the boat with his Disciples, but that his Disciples only were departed.
\v 23 But other boats came in from Tiberias beside the place where they had eaten the bread, our Lord giving thanks. \f + \fr 6:23 \ft These words do plainly import, that the giving thanks was an effectual blessing of the bread and working the multiplication thereof.\f*
\v 24 When therefore the multitude saw that \sc Jesus\sc* was not there, nor his Disciples, they went up into the boats, & came to Capharnaum seeking \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 25 And when they had found him beyond the sea, they said to him: Rabbi, when camest thou hither?
\v 26 \sc Jesus\sc* answered them, and said: Amen, amen I say to you, you seek me not because you have seen signs, but because you did eat of the loaves, and were filled.
\v 27 Work not the meat that perisheth, but that endureth unto life everlasting, which the Son of man will give you. For him the Father, God, hath signed.
\v 28 They said therefore unto him: What shall we do that we may work the works of God?
\v 29 \sc Jesus\sc* answered, and said to them: This is the work of God, that you believe in him whom he hath sent.
\v 30 They said therefore to him: What sign therefore doest thou, that we may see, and may believe thee? what workest thou?
\v 31 Our Fathers did eat Manna in the desert as it is written, \add Bread from Heaven he gave them to eat.\add*
\v 32 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said to them: Amen, amen I say to you, Moyses gave you not the bread from Heaven, but my Father giveth you the true bread from Heaven. \f + \fr 6:32 \ft Why we keep the Hebrew word, Amen, & translate it not, See the Annot. c. 8. vers. 14.\f*
\v 33 For the bread of God it is that descended from Heaven, and giveth life to the world.
\v 34 They said therefore unto him: Lord, give us always this bread.
\v 35 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: I am the bread of life, he that cometh to me, shall not hunger; and he that believeth in me, shall never thirst.
\v 36 But I said to you that both you have seen me and you believe not.
\v 37 All that the Father giveth me, shall come to me; and him that cometh to me I will not cast forth. \f + \fr 6:37 \ft The Gospel in the Anniversary of the dead.\f*
\v 38 Because I descended from Heaven, not to do mine own will, but the will of him that sent me.
\v 39 For this is the will of him that sent me, the Father: that all that he hath given me I leese not thereof, but raise it in the last day.
\v 40 And this is the will of my Father that sent me; that every one that seeth the Son, and believeth in him, have life everlasting, & I will raise him in the last day.
\v 41 The Jews therefore murmured at him, because he had said, I am the bread which descended from Heaven;
\v 42 and they said: Is not this \sc Jesus\sc* the son of Joseph, whose father and mother we know? How then saith he, That I descended from Heaven?
\v 43 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore answered and said to them: Murmur not one to another:
\v 44 no man can come to me, unless the Father that sent me, draw him, and I will raise him up in the last day. \f + \fr 6:44 \ft The Gospel upon Imber Wednesday in Whitsunweek.\f*
\v 45 It is written in the Prophets: \add And all shall be docible of God.\add* Every one that hath heard of the Father, & hath learned, cometh to me.
\v 46 Not that any man hath seen the Father, but he which is of God; this hath seen the Father.
\v 47 Amen, amen I say to you: He that believeth in me, hath life everlasting.
\v 48 I am the bread of life.
\v 49 Your fathers did eat Manna in the desert; and they died.
\v 50 This is the bread that descended from Heaven: that if any man eat of it, he die not.
\v 51 I am the living bread, that came down from Heaven. \f + \fr 6:51 \ft The Gospel in a daily Mass for the dead.\f*
\v 52 If any man eat of this bread, he shall live for ever: and the bread which I will give, is my flesh for the life of the world.
\v 53 The Jews therefore strove among themselves, saying: How can this man give us his flesh to eat?
\v 54 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said to them: Amen, amen I say to you, unless you eat the flesh of the Son of man, and drink his blood, you shall not have life in you.
\v 55 He that eateth my flesh, and drinketh my blood, hath life everlasting; and I will raise him up in the last day.
\v 56 For my flesh, is meat indeed: and my blood is drink indeed. \f + \fr 6:56 \ft The Gospel upon CORPUS CHRISTI day.\f*
\v 57 He that eateth my flesh, and drinketh my blood, abideth in me, and I in him.
\v 58 As the living Father hath sent me, and I live by the Father: and he that eateth me, the same also shall live by me.
\v 59 This is the bread that came down from Heaven. Not as your fathers did eat Manna, and died. He that eateth this bread, shall live for ever.
\v 60 These things he said teaching in the Synagogue, in Capharnaum.
\v 61 Many therefore of his Disciples hearing it, said: This saying is hard, and who can hear it?
\v 62 But \sc Jesus\sc* knowing with himself that his Disciples murmured at this, he said to them: Doth this scandalize you?
\v 63 If then you shall see the Son of man ascend where he was before?
\v 64 It is the spirit that quickeneth, the flesh profiteth nothing. The words that I have spoken to you, be spirit and life.
\v 65 But there be certain of you that believe not. For \sc Jesus\sc* knew from the beginning who they were that did not believe, and who he was that would betray him.
\v 66 And he said: Therefore did I say to you, that no man can come to me, unless it be given him of my Father.
\v 67 After this many of his Disciples went back: and now they walked not with him.
\v 68 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said to the Twelve: What, will you also depart?
\v 69 Simon Peter therefore answered him: Lord, to whom shall we go? thou hast the words of eternal life.
\v 70 And we believe and have known that thou art Christ the Son of God.
\v 71 \sc Jesus\sc* answered them: Have not I chosen you the Twelve; and of you one is a devil?
\v 72 And he meant Judas Iscariot, Simon's son: for this same was to betray him, whereas he was one of the Twelve.
\c 7
\p
\v 1 \sc After\sc* these things \sc Jesus\sc* walked into Galilee, for he would not walk into Jewry: because the Jews sought to kill him. \f + \fr 7:1 \ft The Gospel upon Tuesday in Passion Week.\f* \f + \fr 7:1 \ft in Galilee,\f* \f + \fr 7:1 \ft in Jury:\f*
\v 2 And the festival day of the Jews, Scenopegia, was at hand. \f + \fr 7:2 \ft Scenopegia (Lev. 23. σκηνῶν ἑορτὴ) is the feast of Tabernacles, which the Jews kept from the 7. Octob. for eight days together, by God's commandment, for a memory that their Fathers dwelt by God's protection forty years in tabernacles or tents, and not in houses, coming out of ÆGYPT. See Levit. 23, 34.\f*
\v 3 And his brethren said to him: Pass from hence, and go into Jewry; that thy Disciples also may see thy works which thou doest.
\v 4 For no man doeth any thing in secret, and seeketh himself to be in public. If thou do these things, manifest thyself to the world.
\v 5 For neither did his brethren believe in him.
\v 6 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore saith to them: My time is not yet come; but your time is always ready.
\v 7 The world cannot hate you, but me it hateth: because I give testimony of it, that the works thereof are evil.
\v 8 Go you up to this festival day: I go not up to this festival day; because my time is not yet accomplished. \f + \fr 7:8 \ft I will not yet go up\f*
\v 9 When he had said these things, himself tarried in Galilee.
\v 10 But after his brethren were gone up, then he also went up to the festival day, not openly, but as it were in secret.
\v 11 The Jews therefore sought him in the festival day, and said: Where is he?
\v 12 And there was much murmuring in the multitude of him. For certain said: That he is good. And others said: No, but he seduceth the multitudes.
\v 13 Yet no man spake openly of him for fear of the Jews.
\v 14 And when the festivity was now half done, \sc Jesus\sc* went up into the temple, and taught. \f + \fr 7:14 \ft The Gospel upon Tuesday in the 4. week of Lent.\f*
\v 15 And the Jews marveled, saying: How doth this man know letters, whereas he hath not learned?
\v 16 \sc Jesus\sc* answered them, and said: My doctrine is not mine, but his that sent me.
\v 17 If any man will do the will of him, he shall understand of the doctrine whether it be of God, or I speak of myself. \f + \fr 7:17 \ft The way to come to know the truth, is to live well.\f*
\v 18 He that speaketh of himself, seeketh his own glory. But he that seeketh the glory of him that sent him, he is true, and injustice in him there is not. \f + \fr 7:18 \ft It is spoken of Antichrist specially, and it is true in all Heretics. August. tract. 29. in Evang. Io.\f*
\v 19 Did not Moyses give you the law, and none of you doeth the law?
\v 20 Why seek you to kill me? The multitude answered, and said, Thou hast a devil, who seeketh to kill thee? \f + \fr 7:20 \ft No marvel, when these speak thus to Christ himself, if Heretics call his vicar Antichrist.\f*
\v 21 \sc Jesus\sc* answered and said to them: One work I have done; and you do all marvel.
\v 22 Therefore Moyses gave you circumcision: not that it is of Moyses, but of the fathers, and in the Sabboth you circumcise a man.
\v 23 If a man receive circumcision in the Sabboth, that the law of Moyses be not broken; are you angry at me because I have healed a man wholly in the Sabboth?
\v 24 Judge not according to the face, but judge just judgement.
\v 25 Certain therefore of Jerusalem said: Is not this he whom they seek to kill?
\v 26 And behold, he speaketh openly, and they say nothing to him. Have the Princes known indeed that this is \sc Christ\sc*?
\v 27 But this man we know whence he is. But when \sc Christ\sc* cometh, no man knoweth whence he is.
\v 28 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore cried in the temple teaching and saying: Both me you do know, and whence I am you know. And of myself I am not come, but he is true that sent me, whom you know not.
\v 29 I know him, because I am of him, and he sent me.
\v 30 They sought therefore to apprehend him: and no man laid hands upon him, because his hour was not yet come.
\v 31 But of the multitude many believed in him, and said: \sc Christ\sc*, when he cometh shall he do more signs than these which this man doeth?
\v 32 The Pharisees heard the multitude murmuring these things touching him: and the Princes and Pharisees sent Ministers to apprehend him. \f + \fr 7:32 \ft chief Priests\f*
\v 33 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said to them: Yet a little time I am with you: and I go to him that sent me. \f + \fr 7:33 \ft The Gospel upon Monday in Passion Week.\f*
\v 34 You seek me, and shall not find: and where I am, you cannot come.
\v 35 The Jews therefore said among themselves, whither will this man go, that we shall not find him? will he go into the dispersion of the Gentiles, and teach the Gentiles?
\v 36 What is this saying that he hath said: You shall seek me, and shall not find; and where I am, you cannot come.
\v 37 And in the last, the great day of the festivity \sc Jesus\sc* stood and cried, saying: If any man thirst, let him come to me, and drink.
\v 38 He that believeth in me, as the scripture saith, \add Out of his belly shall flow rivers of living water.\add*
\v 39 (And this he said of the Spirit that they should receive which believed in him. For as yet the Spirit was not given: because \sc Jesus\sc* was not yet glorified.) \f + \fr 7:39 \ft This was fulfilled on Whitsunday Act. 2, & afterward always by imposition of hands in the Sacrament of Confirmation: visibly in the primitive Church, and invisibly to the end of the world.\f*
\v 40 Of that multitude therefore, when they had heard these words of his, some said: This is the Prophet indeed.
\v 41 Others said: This is \sc Christ\sc*. But certain said: Why, doth \sc Christ\sc* come from Galilee?
\v 42 Doth not the scripture say: That of the seed of David, and from Bethlehem the town where David was, \sc Christ\sc* doth come?
\v 43 Therefore there arose dissension in the multitude for him.
\v 44 And certain of them would have apprehended him: but no man laid hands upon him.
\v 45 The ministers therefore came to the chief Priests and the Pharisees. And they said to them: Why have you not brought him?
\v 46 The Ministers answered: Never did there man so speak, as this man.
\v 47 The Pharisees therefore answered them: Why, are you also seduced?
\v 48 Hath any of the Princes believed in him, or of the Pharisees?
\v 49 but this multitude that knoweth not the law, are accursed.
\v 50 Nicodemus said to them, he that came to him by night, who was one of them: \f + \fr 7:50 \ft Christ hath some good always even among the wicked, which secretly serve him and by wise delays avert the execution of unjust laws against him and his people, as Nicodemus & Gamaliel.\f*
\v 51 Doth our law judge a man, unless it first hear him, and know what he doeth?
\v 52 They answered & said to him: Why, art thou also a Galilæan? Search, & see that from Galilee a Prophet riseth not. \f + \fr 7:52 \ft Search the scriptures\f*
\v 53 And every man returned to his house.
\c 8
\p
\v 1 \sc And Jesus\sc* went into the Mount-olivet: \f + \fr 8:1 \ft The Gospel upon Saturday the 3. week of Lent.\f*
\v 2 and early in the morning again he came into the temple, and the people came to him, and sitting he taught them.
\v 3 And the Scribes and Pharisees bring a woman taken in adultery; and they did set her in the midst,
\v 4 And said to him: Master, this woman was even now taken in adultery.
\v 5 And in the law Moyses commanded us to stone such. What sayest thou therefore?
\v 6 And this they said tempting him, that they might accuse him. But \sc Jesus\sc* bowing himself down, with his finger wrote in the earth.
\v 7 When they therefore continued asking him, he lifted up himself, and said to them: He that is without sin of you, let him first throw the stone at her. \f + \fr 8:7 \ft We cannot conveniently reprehend or condemn other men's faults, if ourselves be guilty of the same or other greater. Cyril in Io. See Annot. Mt. 7, 1.\f*
\v 8 And again bowing himself, he wrote in the earth.
\v 9 And they hearing, went out one by one, beginning at the seniors: and \sc Jesus\sc* alone remained, and the woman standing in the midst.
\v 10 And \sc Jesus\sc* lifting up himself, said to her: Woman, where are they that accused thee? Hath no man condemned thee?
\v 11 Who said: No man, Lord. And \sc Jesus\sc* said: Neither will I condemn thee. Go, and now sin no more. \f + \fr 8:11 \ft S. Augustine by this example of our Master proveth that Clergy men specially should be given much to mercy: and that they ought often, as the cause and time require, to get pardon of the secular Magistrates for offenders that be penitent. Ep. 54.\f*
\v 12 Again therefore \sc Jesus\sc* spake to them, saying: I am the light of the world: he that followeth me, walketh not in darkness, but shall have the light of life. \f + \fr 8:12 \ft b The Gospel upon Saturday the 4. Week in Lent.\f*
\v 13 The Pharisees therefore said to him: Thou givest testimony of thyself; thy testimony is not true.
\v 14 \sc Jesus\sc* answered, and said to them: Although I do give testimony of myself, my testimony is true: because I know whence I came, & whither I go: but you know not whence I come, or whither I go.
\v 15 You judge according to the flesh: I do not judge any man.
\v 16 And if I do judge, my judgement is true: because I am not alone, but I and he that sent me, the Father.
\v 17 And in your law it is written, that the testimony of two men is true.
\v 18 I am he that give testimony of myself: and he that sent me, the Father, giveth testimony of me.
\v 19 They said therefore to him: Where is thy Father? \sc Jesus\sc* answered, Neither me do you know, nor my Father. If you did know me, perhaps you might know my Father also.
\v 20 These words \sc Jesus\sc* spake in the Treasury, teaching in the temple, and no man apprehended him, because his hour was not yet come.
\v 21 Again therefore \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: I go, and you shall seek me, and shall die in your sin. Whither I go, you cannot come. \f + \fr 8:21 \ft The Gospel upon Monday the 2. week of Lent.\f*
\v 22 The Jews therefore said: Why, will he kill himself, because he saith: Whither I go, you cannot come?
\v 23 And he said to them: You are from beneath, I am from above. You are of this world, I am not of this world.
\v 24 Therefore I said to you that you shall die in your sins. For if you believe not that I am he, you shall die in your sin.
\v 25 They said therefore to him: Who art thou? \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: The Beginning who also speak to you. \f + \fr 8:25 \ft So read S. Cyril, S. Ambrose, & S. Augustine: expounding it of Christ's person, that he is the beginning or cause of all creatures.\f*
\v 26 Many things I have to speak and judge of you. But he that sent me, is true: and what I have heard of him, these things I speak in the world.
\v 27 And they knew not that he said to them that his Father was God.
\v 28 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said to them: When you shall have exalted the Son of man, then you shall know that I am he, and of myself I do nothing, but as the Father hath taught me, these things I speak:
\v 29 and he that sent me, is with me: and he hath not left me alone, because the things that please him I do always.
\v 30 When he spake these things, many believed in him.
\v 31 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said to them that believed him, the Jews: If you abide in my word, you shall be my Disciples indeed. \f + \fr 8:31 \ft Only faith is not sufficient without perseverance or abiding in the keeping of his commandments.\f*
\v 32 And you shall know the truth, and the truth shall make you free.
\v 33 They answered him: We are the seed of Abraham, and we never served any man: how sayest thou, You shall be free?
\v 34 \sc Jesus\sc* answered them: Amen, amen I say to you, that every one which committeth sin, is the servant of sin.
\v 35 And the servant abideth not in the house for ever: the son abideth for ever.
\v 36 If therefore the Son make you free, you shall be free indeed. \f + \fr 8:36 \ft Man was never without free will: but having the grace of Christ, his will is truly made free (as S. Augustine saith) from servitude of sin also. tract. 41. in Evang. Io.\f*
\v 37 I know that you are the children of Abraham: but you seek to kill me, because my word taketh not in you.
\v 38 Ispeak that which I have seen with my Father: and you do the things that you have seen with your father.
\v 39 They answered, and said to him: Our father is Abraham. \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: If you be the children of Abraham, do the works of Abraham. \f + \fr 8:39 \ft Not only faith but good works also make men the children of Abraham, according as S. James also speaketh of Abraham's works c. 2.\f*
\v 40 But now, you seek to kill me, a man that have spoken the truth to you, which I have heard of God. This did not Abraham.
\v 41 You do the works of your father. They said therefore to him: We were not born of fornication. We have one Father, God.
\v 42 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said to them: If God were your Father, verily you would love me. For from God I proceeded, and came: for I came not of myself, but he sent me:
\v 43 Why do you not know my speech? Because you cannot hear my word.
\v 44 You are of your father the devil, & the desires of your father you will do. He was a man-killer from the beginning, & he stood not in the verity; because verity is not in him. When he speaketh a lie, he speaketh of his own, because he is a liar, & the father thereof. \f + \fr 8:44 \ft S. Augustine compareth Heretics in their spiritual murder by driving Christian men out of the Church, to the Devil that drove our parents out of Paradise. Cont. lit. Petil. li. 2, c. 13.\f*
\v 45 But because I say the verity, you believe me not.
\v 46 Which of you shall argue me of sin? If I say the verity, why do you not believe me?
\v 47 He that is of God, heareth the words of God. Therefore you hear not, because you are not of God. \f + \fr 8:47 \ft The Gospel upon PASSION Sunday.\f*
\v 48 The Jews therefore answered, and said to him: Do not we say well that thou art a Samaritane, and hast a devil?
\v 49 \sc Jesus\sc* answered: I have no devil: but I do honour my Father, and you have dishonoured me. \f + \fr 8:49 \ft He denieth not that he is a Samaritane, because he is our keeper or protector, as the word signifieth, and because he is indeed that merciful Samaritane in the parable of the wounded man Luc. 10, 22. Aug. tract. 43. in Ioan.\f*
\v 50 but I seek not mine own glory. There is that seeketh and judgeth.
\v 51 Amen, amen I say to you: If any man keep my word, he shall not see death for ever.
\v 52 The Jews therefore said: Now we have known that thou hast a devil. Abraham is dead, and the Prophets; and thou sayest: If any man keep my word, he shall not taste death for ever.
\v 53 Why, art thou greater than our father Abraham, who is dead? and the Prophets are dead. Whom doest thou make thyself?
\v 54 \sc Jesus\sc* answered: If I do glorify myself, my glory is nothing. It is my Father that glorifieth me, whom you say that he is your God.
\v 55 And you have not known him, but I know him. And if I shall say that I know him not, I shall be like to you, a liar. But I do know him, and do keep his word.
\v 56 Abraham your father rejoiced that he might see my day: and he saw, and was glad.
\v 57 The Jews therefore said to him: Thou hast not yet fifty years and hast thou seen Abraham?
\v 58 \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: Amen, amen I say to you, before that Abraham was made, I am.
\v 59 They took stones therefore to cast at him. But \sc Jesus\sc* hid himself, and went out of the temple.
\c 9
\p
\v 0 Lord receiveth him: 39. and foretelleth by this occasion, \add the excecation of the Jews (because of their willful obstinacy) and illumination of the Gentiles who confess their own blindness.\add*
\v 1 \sc And Jesus\sc* passing by, saw a man blind: from his nativity; \f + \fr 9:1 \ft The Gospel upon Wednesday in the 4. week of Lent.\f*
\v 2 and his Disciples asked him: Rabbi, who hath sinned, this man, or his parents, that he should be born blind? \sc Jesus\sc* answered:
\v 3 Neither hath this man sinned, nor his parents; but that the works of God may be manifested in him. \f + \fr 9:3 \ft Though many infirmities fall for sin, yet not all: some coming for probation, and some sent that God by the cure thereof may be glorified.\f*
\v 4 I must work the works of him that sent me, whiles it is day. The night cometh, when no man can work. \f + \fr 9:4 \ft The time of working, and meriting, is in this life: after death we can deserve no more by our deeds, but must only receive good or ill, according to the difference of works here.\f*
\v 5 As long as I am in the world, I am the light of the world.
\v 6 When he had said these things, he spit on the ground, and made clay of the spittle, and spread the clay upon his eyes,
\v 7 and said to him: Go, wash in the pool of Siloe, which is interpreted, Sent. He went therefore, and washed; and he came seeing. \f + \fr 9:7 \ft c This was a figure of Baptism, to which all men born in sin and blindness are sent for health & sight. Ambr. li. 3. c. 2. de Sacramentis.\f*
\v 8 Therefore the neighbours, and they which had seen him before, that he was a beggar, said: Is not this he that sat, and begged? Others said: That this is he.
\v 9 But others: No, not so, but he is like him. But he said: That I am he.
\v 10 They said therefore to him: How were thine eyes opened?
\v 11 He answered: That man that is called \sc Jesus\sc*, made clay, and anointed mine eyes, and said to me: Go to the pool of Siloe, and wash. And I went, and washed, and saw.
\v 12 And they said to him: Where is he? He saith: I know not.
\v 13 They bring him that had been blind, to the Pharisees.
\v 14 And it was the Sabboth when \sc Jesus\sc* made the clay, and opened his eyes.
\v 15 Again therefore the Pharisees asked him, how he saw. But he said to them: He put clay upon mine eyes, & I washed; and I see.
\v 16 Certain therefore of the Pharisees said: This man is not of God, that keepeth not the Sabboth. But others said: How can a man that is a sinner do these signs? And there was a schism among them.
\v 17 They say therefore to the blind again: Thou, what sayest thou of him that opened thine eyes? And he said: That he is a Prophet.
\v 18 The Jews therefore did not believe of him, that he had been blind and saw, until they called the parents of him that saw,
\v 19 and asked them, saying: Is this your son, whom you say that he was born blind? how then doth he now see?
\v 20 His parents answered them, and said: We know that this is our son, and that he was born blind;
\v 21 but how he now seeth, we know not, or who hath opened his eyes, we know not, ask himself; he is of age, let himself speak of himself.
\v 22 These things his parents said, because they feared the Jews. For the Jews had now conspired, that if any man should confess him to be \sc Christ\sc*, he should be put out of the Synagogue.
\v 23 Therefore did his parents say: That he is of age, ask himself.
\v 24 They therefore again called the man that had been blind, and said to him: Give glory to God. We know that this man is a sinner. \f + \fr 9:24 \ft So say the Heretics when they derogate from miracles done by Saints or their Relics, pharisaically pretending the glory of God. As though it were not God's glory, when his Saints do it by his power and virtue: yea his greater glory, that doeth such things by his servants, & by the meanest things belonging to them, as Peter's shadow Act. 5. & Paul's napkin Act. 19.\f*
\v 25 He therefore said to them: Whether he be a sinner, I know not: one thing I know, that whereas I was blind, now I see.
\v 26 They said therefore to him: What did he to thee? how did he open thine eyes?
\v 27 He answered them: I have now told you, and you have heard; why will you hear it again? will you also become his Disciples?
\v 28 They reviled him therefore, & said: Be thou his Disciple: but we are the Disciples of Moyses.
\v 29 We know that to Moyses God did speak; but this man we know not whence he is.
\v 30 The man answered and said to them: For in this it is marvelous that you know not whence he is, and he hath opened mine eyes.
\v 31 And we know that sinners God doth not hear. But if a man be a server of God, and do the will of him, him he heareth.
\v 32 From the beginning of the world it hath not been heard that any man hath opened the eyes of one born blind.
\v 33 unless this man were of God, he could not do any thing.
\v 34 They answered and said to him: Thou wast wholly born in sins, and doest thou teach us? And they did cast him forth.
\v 35 \sc Jesus\sc* heard that they cast him forth; & when he had found him, he said to him: Doest thou believe in the Son of God?
\v 36 He answered, and said: Who is he Lord, that I may believe in him?
\v 37 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: Both thou hast seen him; and he that talketh with thee, he it is.
\v 38 But he said, I believe Lord. And falling down he adored him.
\v 39 And \sc Jesus\sc* said to him: For judgement came I into this world; that they that see not, may see: and they that see, may become blind. \f + \fr 9:39 \ft By this we see that this miracle was not only marvelous and beneficial to the blind, but also significative of taking away spiritual blindness.\f*
\v 40 And certain of the Pharisees that were with him, heard; and they said to him: Why, are we also blind?
\v 41 \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: If you were blind, you should not have sin, but now you say, That we see. Your sin remaineth.
\c 10
\p
\v 1 \sc Amen\sc*, amen I say to you, he that entereth not by the door into the fold of the sheep, but climbeth up another way; he is a thief and a robber. \f + \fr 10:1 \ft The Gospel upon Tuesday in Whitsunweek.\f* \f + \fr 10:1 \ft The thief, is the Heretic specially, & any other that unlawfully break in upon the sheep to kill & destroy them by false doctrine and otherwise.\f*
\v 2 But he that entereth by the door, is the Pastor of the sheep.
\v 3 To this man the porter openeth; and the sheep hear his voice: and he calleth his own sheep by name, and leadeth them forth.
\v 4 And when he hath let forth his own sheep, he goeth before them: and the sheep follow him, because they know his voice. \f + \fr 10:4 \ft That is the fashion of Jewry & other countries, signifying that the shepherd or Pastor must teach the sheep, and not they him.\f*
\v 5 But a stranger they follow not, but fly from him because they know not the voice of strangers.
\v 6 This proverb \sc Jesus\sc* said to them. But they knew not what he spake to them.
\v 7 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said to them again: Amen, amen I say to you, that I am the door of the sheep.
\v 8 And how many soever have come, are thieves and robbers: but the sheep heard them not.
\v 9 I am the door. By me if any enter, he shall be saved: & he shall go in and shall go out, & shall find pastures.
\v 10 The thief cometh not but to steal and kill & destroy. I came that they may have life, & may have more aboundantly.
\v 11 I am the good Pastor. \f + \fr 10:11 \ft The Gospel upon the 2. Sunday after Easter, & for S. Thomas of Canterbury. Decemb. 29. And in his Translation. Iulij. 7.\f*
\v 12 The good Pastor giveth his life for his sheep. But the hireling & he that is not the Pastor, whose own the sheep are not, seeth the wolf coming, and leaveth the sheep, and flyeth: and the wolf raveneth, and disperseth the sheep.
\v 13 And the hireling flyeth because he is a hireling; and he hath no care of the sheep.
\v 14 I am the good Pastor; and I know mine, and mine know me.
\v 15 As the Father knoweth me, and I know the Father: and I yield my life for my sheep. \f + \fr 10:15 \ft Christ's death was so necessary for the flock, that when he might have escaped, he voluntarily offered himself to death for his flock.\f*
\v 16 And other sheep I have that are not of this fold: them also I must bring, and they shall hear my voice, and there shall be made one fold and one Pastor.
\v 17 Therefore the Father loveth me: because I yield my life, that I may take it again. \f + \fr 10:17 \ft c He meaneth the Church of the Gentiles.\f*
\v 18 No man taketh it away from me: but I yield it of myself. And I have power to yield it: and I have power to take it again. This commandment I received of my Father.
\v 19 Adissension rose again among the Jews for these words.
\v 20 And many of them said: He hath a devil and is mad; why hear you him?
\v 21 Others said: These are not the words of one that hath a devil. Can a devil open the eyes of blind men?
\v 22 And the Dedication was in Jerusalem: and it was winter.
\v 23 And \sc Jesus\sc* walked in the temple, in Salomon's porch. \f + \fr 10:23 \ft The Gospel upon Wednesday in Passion Week.\f*
\v 24 The Jews therefore compassed him round about, and said to him: How long doest thou hold our soul in suspense? if thou be \sc Christ\sc*, tell us openly.
\v 25 \sc Jesus\sc* answered them: I speak to you; and you believe not; the works that I do in the name of my Father, they give testimony of me.
\v 26 But you do not believe, because you are not of my sheep.
\v 27 My sheep hear my voice; and I know them, and they follow me.
\v 28 And I give them life everlasting; and they shall not perish for ever, and no man shall pluck them out of my hand.
\v 29 My Father, that which he hath given me, is greater than all: and no man can pluck them out of the hand of my Father. \f + \fr 10:29 \ft Another reading is, My father that hath given me, &c.\f*
\v 30 I and the Father are one. \f + \fr 10:30 \ft c unum.\f*
\v 31 The Jews took up stones, to stone him.
\v 32 \sc Jesus\sc* answered them: Many good works I have shewed you from my Father, for which of those works do you stone me?
\v 33 The Jews answered him: For a good work we stone thee not, but for blasphemy, and because thou being a man, makest thyself God.
\v 34 \sc Jesus\sc* answered them: Is it not written in your law, that \add I said, you are gods?\add*
\v 35 If he called them gods, to whom the word of God was made, and the scripture cannot be broken;
\v 36 whom the Father hath sanctified and sent into the world, say you, That thou blasphemest, because I said I am the Son of God?
\v 37 If I do not the works of my Father, believe me not.
\v 38 But if I do, and if you will not believe me, believe the works: that you may know and believe that the Father is in me, and I in the Father.
\v 39 They sought therefore to apprehend him; and he went forth out of their hands.
\v 40 And he went again beyond Jordan into that place where John was baptizing first; and he tarried there.
\v 41 and many came to him, and they said: That John indeed did no sign. But all things whatsoever John said of this man, were true.
\v 42 And many believed in him.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* there was a certain sick man, Lazarus of Bethania, of the town of Mary & Martha her sister. \f + \fr 11:1 \ft The Gospel upon Friday in the 4. week of Lent.\f*
\v 2 (And Mary was she that anointed our Lord with ointment, & wiped his feet with her hair: whose brother Lazarus was sick.)
\v 3 His sisters therefore sent to him saying: Lord, behold, he whom thou lovest, is sick.
\v 4 And \sc Jesus\sc* hearing, said to them: This sickness is not to death, but for the glory of God: that the Son of God may be glorified by it.
\v 5 And \sc Jesus\sc* loved Martha, and her sister Mary, and Lazarus.
\v 6 As he heard therefore that he was sick, then he tarried in the same place two days:
\v 7 then after this he saith to his Disciples: Let us go into Jewry again.
\v 8 The Disciples say to him: Rabbi, now the Jews sought to stone thee; and goest thou thither again?
\v 9 \sc Jesus\sc* answered: Are there not twelve hours of the day? If a man walk in the day, he stumbleth not: because he seeth the light of this world:
\v 10 but if he walk in the night, he stumbleth, because the light is not in him.
\v 11 These things he said; and after this he saith to them: Lazarus our friend sleepeth; but I go that I may raise him from sleep.
\v 12 His Disciples therefore said: Lord, if he sleep, he shall be safe.
\v 13 But \sc Jesus\sc* spake of his death; & they thought that he spake of the sleeping of sleep. \f + \fr 11:13 \ft c de dormitione somni.\f*
\v 14 Then therefore \sc Jesus\sc* said to them plainly: Lazarus is dead;
\v 15 and I am glad for your sake, that you may believe, because I was not there: but let us go to him.
\v 16 Thomas therefore, who is called Didymus, said to his condisciples: Let us also go, to die with him.
\v 17 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore came, and found him now having been four days in the grave.
\v 18 (And Bethania was nigh to Jerusalem about fifteen furlongs.)
\v 19 And many of the Jews were come to Martha and Mary, to comfort them concerning their brother.
\v 20 Martha therefore when she heard that \sc Jesus\sc* was come, went to meet him; but Mary sat at home.
\v 21 Martha therefore said to \sc Jesus\sc*: Lord if thou hadst been here, my brother had not died. \f + \fr 11:21 \ft The Gospel in a Mass for the dead upon the day of the burial or deposition, also the 3. 7. and 30. day.\f*
\v 22 But now also I know that what things soever thou shalt ask of God, God will give thee.
\v 23 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to her: Thy brother shall rise again.
\v 24 Martha saith to him: I know that he shall rise again in the resurrection, in the last day.
\v 25 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to her: I am the resurrection and the life; he that believeth in me, although he be dead, shall live.
\v 26 And every one that liveth, and believeth in me, shall not die for ever. Believest thou this?
\v 27 She saith to him: Yea Lord, I have believed that thou art \sc Christ\sc* the Son of God that art come into this world.
\v 28 And when she had said these things, she went, and called Mary her sister secretly, saying: The Master is come, & calleth thee.
\v 29 She, when she heard, riseth quickly & cometh to him.
\v 30 For \sc Jesus\sc* was not yet come into the town: but he was yet in that place where Martha had met him.
\v 31 The Jews therefore that were with her in the house and did comfort her, when they saw Mary that she rose quickly and went forth, followed her, saying: That she goeth to the grave, to weep there.
\v 32 Mary therefore when she was come where \sc Jesus\sc* was, seeing him, fell at his feet, and saith to him: Lord, if thou hadst been here, my brother had not died.
\v 33 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore when he saw her, weeping, and the Jews that were come with her, weeping, he groaned in spirit, and troubled himself,
\v 34 and said: Where have you laid him? They say to him: Lord, come and see.
\v 35 And \sc Jesus\sc* wept.
\v 36 The Jews therefore said: Behold how he loved him.
\v 37 But certain of them said: Could not he that opened the eyes of the blind man, make that this man should not die?
\v 38 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore again groaning in himself, cometh to the grave: and it was a cave; and a stone was laid over it.
\v 39 \sc Jesus\sc* saith: Take away the stone. Martha the sister of him that was dead, said to him: Lord, now he stinketh, for he is now of four days.
\v 40 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to her: Did not I say to thee, that if thou believe, thou shalt see the glory of God?
\v 41 They took therefore the stone away. And \sc Jesus\sc* lifting his eyes upward, said: Father, I give thee thanks that thou hast heard me.
\v 42 And I did know that thou doest always hear me, but for the people that standeth about, have I said it, that they may believe that thou hast sent me.
\v 43 When he had said these things, he cried with a loud voice: Lazarus, come forth.
\v 44 And forthwith he came forth that had been dead, bound feet and hands with winding bands, and his face was tied with a napkin. \sc Jesus\sc* said to them: Loose him, and let him go. \f + \fr 11:44 \ft S. Cyril li. 7. c. ult. in Io. and S. August. Tract. 49. in Io. apply this to the Apostles and Priest's authority of absolving sinners: affirming Christ to revive none from sin, but in the Church and by the Priest's ministry.\f*
\v 45 Many therefore of the Jews that were come to Mary & Martha, & had seen the things that \sc Jesus\sc* did, believed in him.
\v 46 And certain of them went to the Pharisees, & told them the things that \sc Jesus\sc* did.
\v 47 The chief Priests therefore & the Pharisees gathered a Council, & said: What do we, for this man doeth many signs. \f + \fr 11:47 \ft The Gospel upon Friday in Passion Week.\f*
\v 48 If we let him alone so, all will believe in him: & the Romans will come, & take away our place & nation. \f + \fr 11:48 \ft All men, but specially Nations must take heed, that whiles to save their temporal state, they forsake God, they lose not both as the Jews did. Aug. tract. 49. in Io.\f*
\v 49 But one of them named Caiphas, being the high Priest of that year, said to them: You know nothing,
\v 50 neither do you consider: that it is expedient for us that one man die for the people, & the whole nation perish not.
\v 51 And this he said not of himself: but being the high Priest of that year, he prophesied that \sc Jesus\sc* should die for the nation.
\v 52 And not only for the nation, but to gather into one the children of God that were dispersed.
\v 53 From that day therefore they devised to kill him.
\v 54 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore walked no more openly among the Jews, but he went into the country beside the desert unto a city that is called Ephrem, and there he abode with his Disciples.
\v 55 And the Pasch of the Jews was at hand: & many of the country went up to Jerusalem before the Pasch to sanctify themselves.
\v 56 They sought \sc Jesus\sc* therefore; and they communed one with another, standing in the temple: What think you, in that he is not come to the festival day? And the chief Priests & Pharisees had given commandment, that if any man should know where he was, he should tell, that they might apprehend him.
\c 12
\p
\v 1 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore six days before the Pasch came to Bethania, where Lazarus was, that had been dead, whom \sc Jesus\sc* raised. \f + \fr 12:1 \ft The Gospel upon Monday in Holy Week.\f*
\v 2 And they made him a supper there: and Martha ministered, but Lazarus was one of them that sat at the table with him. \f + \fr 12:2 \ft PALM SUNDAY eve.\f*
\v 3 Mary therefore took a pound of ointment of right spikenard, precious, and anointed the feet of \sc Jesus\sc*, and wiped his feet with her hair: and the house was filled of the odour of the ointment. \f + \fr 12:3 \ft Of this woman's extraordinary offices of devotion, & how acceptable they were to Christ, see the Annot. Mt. 26.\f*
\v 4 One therefore of his Disciples, Judas Iscariote, he that was to betray him, said:
\v 5 Why was not this ointment sold for three-hundred pence, and given to the poor?
\v 6 And he said this, not because he cared for the poor; but because he was a thief, and having the purse, carried the things that were put in.
\v 7 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said: Let her alone that she may keep it for the day of my burial. \f + \fr 12:7 \ft The devout offices of balming and anointing the dead\f*
\v 8 For the poor you have always with you; but me you shall not have always. \f + \fr 12:8 \ft Not in visible and mortal condition, to receive alms of you or such like offices for supply of my necessities.\f*
\v 9 A great multitude therefore of the Jews knew that he was there; and they came, not for \sc Jesus\sc* only, but that they might see Lazarus, whom he raised from the dead.
\v 10 But the chief Priests devised for to kill Lazarus also:
\v 11 because many for him of the Jews went away, and believed in \sc Jesus\sc*. \f + \fr 12:11 \ft The Gospel upon Saturday in Passion Week.\f*
\v 12 And on the morrow a great multitude that was come to the festival day, when they had heard that \sc Jesus\sc* cometh to Jerusalem, \f + \fr 12:12 \ft PALM SUNDAY.\f*
\v 13 they took the boughs of palms, and went forth to meet him, & cried: \add Hosanna, Blessed is he that cometh in the name of our Lord, the King of Israel.\add*
\v 14 And \sc Jesus\sc* found a young ass, and sat upon it, as it is written:
\v 15 \add Fear not daughter of Sion: behold, thy King cometh sitting upon an ass's colt.\add*
\v 16 These things his Disciples did not know at the first: but when \sc Jesus\sc* was glorified, then they remembered that these things had been written of him, and these things they did to him.
\v 17 The multitude therefore gave testimony, which was with him when he called Lazarus out of the grave, and raised him from the dead.
\v 18 For therefore also the multitude came to meet him, because they heard that he had done this sign.
\v 19 The Pharisees therefore said among themselves: Do you see that we prevail nothing? Behold the whole world is gone after him.
\v 20 And there were certain Gentiles of them that came up to adore in the festival day. \f + \fr 12:20 \ft We may see there is a great difference where a man pray or adore, at home or in the Church & holy places: when the Gentiles also came of devotion a pilgrimage to the Temple in Hierusalem.\f*
\v 21 These therefore came to Philippe who was of Bethsaida of Galilee, and desired him, saying: Sir, we are desirous to see \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 22 Philippe cometh and telleth Andrew. Again Andrew & Philippe told \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 23 But \sc Jesus\sc* answered them, saying: The hour is come, that the Son of man shall be glorified.
\v 24 Amen, amen I say to you, unless the grain of wheat falling into the ground, die: itself remaineth alone. but if it die, it bringeth much fruit. \f + \fr 12:24 \ft b The Gospel for S. Ignatius Febr. 1. And S. Laurence Aug. 10. And for some other martyrs not Bishops.\f*
\v 25 He that loveth his life shall lose it: and he that hateth his life in this world, doth keep it to life everlasting.
\v 26 If any man minister to me, let him follow me: and where I am, there also shall my minister be. If any man minister to me, my Father will honour him.
\v 27 Now my soul is troubled. And what shall I say? Father, save me from this hour. But therefore came I into this hour.
\v 28 Father, glorify thy name. A voice therefore came from Heaven: Both I have glorified it, and again I will glorify it.
\v 29 The multitude therefore that stood and had heard, said that it thundered. Others said, An Angel spake to him.
\v 30 \sc Jesus\sc* answered, and said: This voice came not for me, but for your sake.
\v 31 Now is the judgement of the world: now the Prince of this world shall be cast forth. \f + \fr 12:31 \ft The Gospel upon Holy Rood day Septemb. 14. in Latin, Exaltatio S. Crucis.\f*
\v 32 And I, if I be exalted from the earth, will draw all things to myself.
\v 33 (And this he said, signifying what death he should die.)
\v 34 The multitude answered him: We have heard out of the law, that \sc Christ\sc* abideth for ever; and how sayest thou: The Son of man must be exalted? Who is this Son of man?
\v 35 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said to them: Yet a little while, the light is among you. Walk whiles you have the light, that the darkness overtake you not. And he that walketh in darkness, knoweth not whither he goeth.
\v 36 Whiles you have the light, believe in the light, that you may be the children of light. These things \sc Jesus\sc* spake and he went away, and hid himself from them.
\v 37 And whereas he had done so many signs before them, they believed not in him:
\v 38 that the saying of Esay the Prophet might be fulfilled, which he said: \add Lord, who hath believed the hearing of us? and the arm of our Lord to whom hath it been revealed?\add*
\v 39 Therefore they could not believe, because Esay said again: \f + \fr 12:39 \ft If any man ask (saith S. Augustine) why they could not believe: I answer roundly, because they would not. Tract. 33. in Io. See the meaning of this speech Annot. Mat. 13. 15. Mar. 4, 12.\f*
\v 40 \add He hath blinded their eyes, and indurated their heart: that they may not see with their eyes, nor understand with their heart, and be converted, and I heal them.\add*
\v 41 These things said Esaie, when he saw his glory, & spake of him.
\v 42 But yet of the Princes also many believed in him: but for the Pharisees they did not confess, that they might not be cast out of the Synagogue. \f + \fr 12:42 \ft This is the case of many principal men in such countries where heresy hath the upper-hand. Who know and believe the Catholic faith: but making choice rather to keep man's favour than God's, they dare not confess the same. Such may pray that God and the world agree together: for else it is seen whose part they will take.\f*
\v 43 For they loved the glory of men more, than the glory of God.
\v 44 But \sc Jesus\sc* cried, and said: He that believeth in me, doth not believe in me, but in him that sent me.
\v 45 And he that seeth me, seeth him that sent me.
\v 46 I a light am come into this world: that every one which believeth in me, may not remain in the darkness.
\v 47 And if any man hear my words, and keep them not: I do not judge him. For I came not to judge the world, but to save the world.
\v 48 He that despiseth me, & receiveth not my words, hath that judgeth him. the word that I have spoken, that shall judge him in the last day.
\v 49 Because of myself I have not spoken, but the Father that sent me, he gave me commandment what I should say, and what I should speak.
\v 50 And I know that his commandment is life everlasting. The things therefore that I speak: as the Father said to me, so do I speak.
\c 13
\p
\v 0 Peter who presumed too much of his own strength, that \add even this night he will deny him thrice.\add*
\v 1 \sc And\sc* before the festival day of Pasch, \sc Jesus\sc* knowing that his hour was come that he should pass out of this world to his Father: whereas he had loved his that were in the world, unto the end he loved them. \f + \fr 13:1 \ft The Gospel upon Maundy Thursday at Mass, & at the washing of feet.\f* \f + \fr 13:1 \ft MAUNDY THURSDAY.\f*
\v 2 And when supper was done, whereas the devil now had put into the heart of Judas Iscariote the son of Simon, to betray him: \f + \fr 13:2 \ft By supper, he meaneth the eating of the Paschal lamb. For, the institution of the B. Sacrament was after this.\f*
\v 3 knowing that the Father gave him all things into his hands, & that he came from God, and goeth to God:
\v 4 he riseth from supper, and layeth aside his garments, and having taken a towel, girded himself.
\v 5 After that, he put water into a basin, and began to wash the feet of the Disciples, and to wipe them with the towel where with he was girded.
\v 6 He cometh therefore to Simon Peter. And Peter saith to him; Lord: doest thou wash my feet?
\v 7 \sc Jesus\sc* answered and said to him: That which I do, thou knowest not now, hereafter thou shalt know.
\v 8 Peter saith to him: Thou shalt not wash my feet for ever. \sc Jesus\sc* answered him: If I wash thee not, thou shalt not have part with me.
\v 9 Simon Peter saith to him: Lord, not only my feet, but also hands, and head.
\v 10 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: He that is washed, needeth not but to wash his feet, but is clean wholly. And you are clean, but not all.
\v 11 For he knew who he was that would betray him. therefore he said: You are not clean all.
\v 12 Therefore, after he had washed their feet, and taken his garments, being set down, again he said to them: Know you what I have done to you?
\v 13 You call me, Master, and Lord: and you say well, for I am so.
\v 14 If then I have washed your feet, Lord and Master; you also ought to wash one another's feet.
\v 15 For I have given you an example, that as I have done to you, so you do also.
\v 16 Amen, amen I say to you, a servant is not greater than his Lord, neither is an Apostle greater than he that sent him.
\v 17 If you know these things, you shall be blessed if you do them.
\v 18 Ispeak not of you all: I know whom I have chosen. But that the scripture may be fulfilled, \add He that eateth bread with me shall lift up his heel against me.\add*
\v 19 From this time I tell you, before it come to pass: that when it shall come to pass, you may believe, that I am he.
\v 20 Amen, amen, I say to you, he that receiveth any that I send, receiveth me: & he that receiveth me, receiveth him that sent me.
\v 21 When \sc Jesus\sc* had said these things, he was troubled in spirit: and he protested, and said: Amen, amen I say to you that one of you shall betray me.
\v 22 The Disciples therefore looked one upon another, doubting of whom he spake.
\v 23 There was therefore one of his Disciples leaning in the bosom of \sc Jesus\sc*, he whom \sc Jesus\sc* loved.
\v 24 Therefore Simon Peter beckoneth to him, and said to him: Who is it of whom he speaketh?
\v 25 He therefore leaning upon the breast of \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: Lord, who is he?
\v 26 \sc Jesus\sc* answered: He it is to whom I shall reach the dipped bread. And when he had dipped the bread, he gave it to Judas Iscariote Simon's son.
\v 27 And after the morsel, then Satan entered into him. And \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: That which thou doest, do it quickly.
\v 28 But no man knew of those that sat at table to what purpose he said this unto him.
\v 29 For certain thought, because Judas had the purse, that \sc Jesus\sc* had said to him: Buy those things which are needful for us to the festival day: or that he should give something to the poor. \f + \fr 13:29 \ft Christ had some provision before hand given him by the Collections of the faithful, which was used both in his own necessities, & bestowed upon the poor.\f*
\v 30 He therefore having received the morsel, incontinent went forth. And it was night.
\v 31 When he therefore was gone forth, \sc Jesus\sc* said: Now the Son of man is glorified, and God is glorified in him.
\v 32 If God be glorified in him, God also will glorify him in himself, and incontinent will he glorify him.
\v 33 Little children, yet a little while I am with you. You shall seek me, & as I said to the Jews, whither I go, you cannot come: to you also I say now.
\v 34 A new commandment I give to you, That you love one another; as I have loved you, that you also love one another.
\v 35 In this all men shall know that you are my Disciples, if you have love one to another.
\v 36 Simon Peter saith to him: Lord, whither goest thou? \sc Jesus\sc* answered, Whither I go, thou canst not now follow me, but hereafter thou shalt follow.
\v 37 Peter saith to him: Why cannot I follow thee now? I will yield my life for thee.
\v 38 \sc Jesus\sc* answered him: Thy life wilt thou yield for me? Amen, amen I say to thee, the cock shall not crow, until thou deny me thrice.
\c 14
\p
\v 1 \sc Let\sc* not your heart be troubled. You believe in God, believe in me also. \f + \fr 14:1 \ft The Gospel upon SS. Philip and Jacob's day Maii. 1.\f*
\v 2 In my Father's house there be many mansions. If not, I would have told you, Because I go to prepare you a place. \f + \fr 14:2 \ft These mansions signify differences of glory in heaven. Hiero. li. 2. adv. Iovin.\f*
\v 3 And if I go, and prepare you a place: I come again and will take you to myself, that where I am, you also may be.
\v 4 And whither I go you know, and the way you know.
\v 5 Thomas saith to him: Lord, we know not whither thou goest; and how can we know the way?
\v 6 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: I am the way, and the verity, and the life. No man cometh to the Father; but by me.
\v 7 If you had known me, my Father also certes you had known: and from hence forth you shall know him, and you have seen him. \f + \fr 14:7 \ft do know\f*
\v 8 Philippe saith to him: Lord shew us the Father, and it sufficeth us.
\v 9 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: So long time I am with you; & have you not known me? Philippe, he that seeth me, seeth the Father also. How sayest thou, Shew us the Father?
\v 10 Doest thou not believe that I am in the Father, & the Father in me? The words that I speak to you, of myself I speak not. But my Father that abideth in me, he doeth the works. \f + \fr 14:10 \ft do ye not believe.\f*
\v 11 Believe you not, that I am in the Father and the Father in me? Otherwise for the works themselves believe.
\v 12 Amen, amen I say to you, he that believeth in me, the works that I do, he also shall do, and greater than these shall he do,
\v 13 because I go to the Father, & whatsoever you shall ask in my name, that will I do: that the Father may be glorified in the Son.
\v 14 If you ask me any thing in my name, that will I do. \f + \fr 14:14 \ft The Gospel in a votive Mass for the election of the Pope, & upon Whitsuneve.\f*
\v 15 If you love me, keep my commandments. \f + \fr 14:15 \ft It is then possible both to love Christ, and to keep his commandments.\f*
\v 16 And I will ask the Father, and he will give you another Paraclete, that he may abide with you for ever, \f + \fr 14:16 \ft c Paraclete by interpretation is either a comforter, or an advocate: and therefore to translate it by any one of them only, is perhaps to abridge the sense of this place.\f*
\v 17 the Spirit of truth, whom the world cannot receive, because it seeth him not, neither knoweth him, but you know him: because he shall abide with you, and shall be in you. \f + \fr 14:17 \ft shall know\f*
\v 18 I will not leave you orphans: I will come to you.
\v 19 Yet a little while: and the world seeth me no more. But you see me: because I live, and you shall live.
\v 20 In that day you shall know that I am in my Father, and you in me; and I in you.
\v 21 He that hath my commandments, & keepeth them: he it is that loveth me. And he that loveth me, shall be loved of my Father: and I will love him, and will manifest myself to him.
\v 22 Judas saith to him, not that Iscariote: Lord, what is done, that thou wilt manifest thyself to us, and not to the world?
\v 23 \sc Jesus\sc* answered, and said to him: If any love me, he will keep my word, and my Father will love him, and we will come to him, and will make abode with him. \f + \fr 14:23 \ft The Gospel upon Whitsunday. And in a votive Mass of the Holy Ghost.\f*
\v 24 He that loveth me not, keepeth not my words. And the word which you have heard, is not mine; but his that sent me, the Father's.
\v 25 These things have I spoken to you abiding with you.
\v 26 But the Paraclete the Holy Ghost, whom the Father will send in my name, he shall teach you all things, & suggest unto you all things whatsoever I shall say to you. \f + \fr 14:26 \ft See the Annot. upon the 16. Chap. vers. 12. & 13.\f*
\v 27 Peace I leave to you, my peace I give to you; not as the world giveth, do I give to you. Let not your heart be troubled, nor fear.
\v 28 You have heard that I said to you, I go, and I come to you. If you loved me, you would be glad verily, that I go to the Father: because the Father is greater than I.
\v 29 And now I have told you before it come to pass: that when it shall come to pass, you may believe.
\v 30 Now I will not speak many things with you. For the Prince of this world cometh, and in me he hath not any thing.
\v 31 But that the world may know that I love the Father: and as the Father hath given me commandment, so do I: Arise, let us go hence.
\c 15
\p
\v 1 I AM the true vine; and my Father is the husband-man. \f + \fr 15:1 \ft The Gospel for some Martyrs, between Easter & Whitsunday. And on SS. Simon and Jude's eve. Oct. 27.\f* \f + \fr 15:1 \ft The Gospel upon S. George's day: April. 23. And for some other Martyrs between Easter & Whitsunday.\f*
\v 2 Every branch in me, not bearing fruit, he will take it away: & every one that beareth fruit, he will purge it, that it may bring more fruit. \f + \fr 15:2 \ft Christ hath some branches in his body mystical that be fruitless. Therefore ill livers also may be members of Christ & the Church.\f* \f + \fr 15:2 \ft Man may continually increase in justice and sanctification, so long as he liveth.\f*
\v 3 Now you are clean for the word which I have spoken to you. \f + \fr 15:3 \ft S. Augustine expoundeth it of the Sacramental word of Baptism, and not as Heretics do, of preaching only. Tract. 80. in Io.\f*
\v 4 Abide in me: and I in you. As the branch cannot bear fruit of itself, unless it abide in the vine, so you neither unless you abide in me.
\v 5 I am the vine: you the branches. He that abideth in me, and I in him, the same beareth much fruit: for without me you can do nothing.
\v 6 If any abide not in me: he shall be cast forth as the branch, and shall wither, and they shall gather him up, and cast him into the fire, and he burneth.
\v 7 If you abide in me, & my words abide in you: you shall ask what thing soever you will, and it shall be done to you. \f + \fr 15:7 \ft If a Schismatic pray never so much, he is not heard, because he remaineth not in the body of Christ.\f*
\v 8 In this my Father is glorified; that you bring very much fruit, and become my Disciples.
\v 9 As my Father hath loved me, I also have loved you. Abide in my love.
\v 10 If you keep my precepts, you shall abide in my love: as I also have kept my Father's precepts, and do abide in his love.
\v 11 These things I have spoken to you, that my joy may be in you, and your joy may be filled.
\v 12 This is my precept, that you love one another, as I have loved you.
\v 13 Greater love than this no man hath, that a man yield his life for his friends. \f + \fr 15:13 \ft The Gospel upon S. Barnabee's day, and on the eves of some Apostles.\f*
\v 14 You are my friends, if you do the things that I command you.
\v 15 Now I call you not servants: for the servant knoweth not what his Lord doeth. But you I have called friends; because all things whatsoever I heard of my Father, I have notified unto you.
\v 16 You chose not me, but I chose you; and have appointed you: that you go, & bring fruit; and your fruit abide: that whatsoever you ask the Father in my name, he may give it you.
\v 17 These things I command you, that you love one another.
\v 18 If the world hate you, know ye that it hath hated me before you. \f + \fr 15:18 \ft The Gospel upon SS. Simon and Jude's day. Octob. 28.\f*
\v 19 If you had been of the world, the world would love his own. But because you are not of the world, but I have chosen you out of the world, therefore the world hateth you.
\v 20 Remember my word that I said to you: The servant is not greater than his Master. If they have persecuted me, you also will they persecute. If they have kept my word, yours also will they keep. \f + \fr 15:20 \ft He foresheweth that many will not obey the Church's words; & no marvel, because they contemned Christ's own precepts.\f*
\v 21 But all these things they will do to you for my name sake; because they know not him that sent me.
\v 22 If I had not come, and spoken to them, they should not have sin: but now they have no excuse of their sin.
\v 23 He that hateth me, hateth my Father also.
\v 24 If I had not done among them works that no other man hath done, they should not have sin: but now both they have seen, and they do hate both me and my Father.
\v 25 But that the word may be fulfilled, which is written in their law: \add That they hated me gratis.\add*
\v 26 But when the Paraclete cometh whom I will send you from the Father, the Spirit of truth, which proceedeth from the Father, he shall give testimony of me: \f + \fr 15:26 \ft The Gospel upon Sunday within the Octave, of the Ascension. And in a Votive of the B. Trinity.\f*
\v 27 and you shall give testimony, because you are with me from the beginning.
\c 16
\p
\v 0 apprehension, they will all forsake him.
\v 1 \sc These\sc* things have I spoken to you, that you be not scandalized.
\v 2 Out of the Synagogues they will cast you: but the hour cometh, that every one which killeth you, shall think that he doeth service to God. \f + \fr 16:2 \ft The Heretics translate, Excommunicate you. See what corruption this is, and the reason thereof, Annot. c. 9, 22.\f*
\v 3 And these things they will do to you, because they have not known the Father, nor me.
\v 4 But these things I have spoken to you: that when the hour shall come, you may remember them, that I told you.
\v 5 But I told you not these things from the beginning, because I was with you. And now I go to him that sent me, and none of you asketh me: Whither goest thou?
\v 6 But because I have spoken these things to you, sorrow hath filled your heart. \f + \fr 16:6 \ft The Gospel upon the 4. Sunday after Easter.\f*
\v 7 But I tell you the truth, it is expedient for you that I go. For if I go not, the Paraclete shall not come to you: but if I go, I will send him to you.
\v 8 And when he is come, he shall argue the world of sin, and of justice, and of judgement.
\v 9 Of sin: because they believed not in me.
\v 10 But of justice: because I go to the Father; and now you shall not see me.
\v 11 And of judgement: because the Prince of this world is now judged.
\v 12 Yet many things I have to say to you: but you cannot bear them now.
\v 13 But when he, the Spirit of truth, cometh, he shall teach you all truth. For he shall not speak of himself; but what things soever he shall hear, he shall speak: and the things that are to come he shall shew you. \f + \fr 16:13 \ft If he shall teach all truth, & that for ever (as before c. 14, 16:) how is it possible, that the Church can err, or hath erred at any time or in any point?\f*
\v 14 He shall glorify me; because he shall receive of mine, and shall shew to you.
\v 15 All things whatsoever the Father hath, be mine. Therefore I said, that he shall receive of mine, and shall shew to you.
\v 16 A little while, and now you shall not see me; & again a little while, & you shall see me: because I go to the Father. \f + \fr 16:16 \ft The Gospel upon the 3. Sunday after Easter.\f*
\v 17 Some therefore of his Disciples said one to another: What is this that he saith to us: A little while, and you shall not see me; and again a little while and you shall see me, and, because I go to the Father?
\v 18 They said therefore: What is this that he saith, A little while? we know not what he speaketh.
\v 19 And \sc Jesus\sc* knew, that they would ask him; & he said to them: Of this you do question among yourselves, because I said to you: A little while, and you shall not see me; and again a little while, and you shall see me.
\v 20 Amen, amen I say to you, that you shall weep and lament, but the world shall rejoice: and you shall be made sorrowful, but your sorrow shall be turned into joy. \f + \fr 16:20 \ft The Gospel for some Martyrs between Easter. & Whitsunday.\f*
\v 21 Awoman when she travaileth, hath sorrow, because her hour is come: but when she hath brought forth the child, now she remembereth not the anguish for joy, that a man is born into the world.
\v 22 And you therefore, now indeed you have sorrow, but I will see you again, and your heart shall rejoice; and your joy no man shall take from you.
\v 23 And in that day me you shall not ask any thing. Amen, amen I say to you, if you ask the Father any thing in my name, he will give it you. \f + \fr 16:23 \ft The Gospel upon the 5. Sunday after Easter.\f* \f + \fr 16:23 \ft Upon this the Church concludeth all her prayers, Per Christum Dominum nostrum, even those also that be made to Saints.\f*
\v 24 Until now you have not asked any thing in my name. Ask and you shall receive; that your joy may be full.
\v 25 These things in proverbs I have spoken to you. The hour cometh when in proverbs I will no more speak to you, but plainly of the Father I will shew you.
\v 26 In that day you shall ask in my name: and I say not to you, that I will ask the Father for you.
\v 27 For the Father himself loveth you, because you have loved me, and have believed that I came forth from God.
\v 28 I came forth from the Father, and came into the world: again I leave the world, and I go to the Father.
\v 29 His Disciples say to him: Behold now thou speakest plainly, and sayest no proverb.
\v 30 Now we know that thou knowest all things, and thou needest not that any man ask thee. In this we believe that thou camest forth from God.
\v 31 \sc Jesus\sc* answered them: Now do you believe?
\v 32 Behold the hour cometh, and it is now come, that you shall be scattered every man into his own, and me you shall leave alone: and I am not alone because the Father is with me.
\v 33 These things I have spoken to you, that in me you may have peace. In the world you shall have distress, but have confidence, I have overcome the world.
\c 17
\p
\v 1 \sc These\sc* things spake \sc Jesus\sc*: and lifting up his eyes into Heaven, he said: Father, the hour is come, glorify thy Son, that thy Son may glorify thee. \f + \fr 17:1 \ft The Gospel upon Ascension eve.\f* \f + \fr 17:1 \ft The Father glorifieth the Son by raising him from death, exalting him up to his right hand, making all creatures to bow down at his Name, and giving him all powers and judgement. The Son again glorifieth the Father, by making his honour, which only in a manner was in Jewry before, now known to all Nations.\f*
\v 2 As thou hast given him power over all flesh, that all which thou hast given him, to them he may give life everlasting.
\v 3 And this is life everlasting that they know thee, the only true God, and whom thou hast sent \sc Jesus Christ\sc*.
\v 4 I have glorified thee upon the earth: I have consummated the work which thou gavest me to do:
\v 5 and now glorify thou me O Father with thyself, with the glory which I had before the world was, with thee.
\v 6 I have manifested thy name to the men whom thou gavest me out of the world. Thine they were, and to me thou gavest them: and they have kept thy word.
\v 7 Now they have known that all things which thou gavest me are from thee:
\v 8 because the words which thou gavest me, I have given them: and they have received, and known in very deed that I came forth from thee, and have believed that thou didst send me.
\v 9 For them do I pray: Not for the world do I pray, but for them whom thou hast given me;
\v 10 because they be thine: and all things be thine, and thine be mine: and I am glorified in them. And now I am not in the world, and these are in the world, & I come to thee.
\v 11 Holy father, keep them in thy name, whom thou hast given me; that they may be one, as also we. \f + \fr 17:11 \ft The Gospel in a votive Mass against Schism.\f* \f + \fr 17:11 \ft His petition is specially to keep the Apostles and his Church in unity and from Schisms.\f*
\v 12 When I was with them, I kept them in thy name. Those whom thou gavest me, have I kept: and none of them perished, but the son of perdition, that the scripture may be fulfilled.
\v 13 And now I come to thee: and these things I speak in the world, that they may have my joy filled in themselves.
\v 14 I have given them thy word, and the world hath hated them, because they are not of the world: as I also am not of the world.
\v 15 I pray not that thou take them away out of the world, but that thou preserve them from evil.
\v 16 Of the world they are not: as I also am not of the world.
\v 17 Sanctify them in truth. Thy word is truth.
\v 18 As thou didst send me into the world, I also have sent them into the world.
\v 19 And for them I do sanctify myself: that they also may be sanctified in truth. \f + \fr 17:19 \ft To sanctify himself, is to sacrifice himself, by dedicating his holy body and blood to his Father, both upon the Cross, and in the holy Sacrament.\f*
\v 20 And not for them only do I pray, but for them also that by their word shall believe in me:
\v 21 that they all may be one, as thou (Father) in me & I in thee; that they also in us may be one: that the world may believe that thou hast sent me.
\v 22 And the glory that thou hast given me, have I given to them; that they may be one as we also are one.
\v 23 I in them, and thou in me: that they may be consummate in one: and the world may know that thou hast sent me, and hast loved them, as me also thou hast loved.
\v 24 Father, whom thou hast given me, I will, that where I am, they also may be with me: that they may see my glory which thou hast given me, because thou hast loved me before the creation of the world.
\v 25 Just Father, the world hath not known thee. But I have known thee: and these have known, that thou didst send me.
\v 26 And I have notified thy name to them, and will notify it: that the love wherewith thou hast loved me may be in them, and I in them.
\c 18
\p
\v 1 \sc When Jesus\sc* had said these things, he went forth with his Disciples beyond the Torrent-Cedron, where was a garden, into the which he entered and his Disciples. \f + \fr 18:1 \ft THURSDAY night. The PASSION according to S. John in these two Chapters, is the Gospel at Mass upon Good Friday. So the PASSION is read in Holy Week four times, according to the four Evangelists, as S. Augustine appointed also in his Church at Hippo. Ser. 144. de tempore.\f*
\v 2 And Judas also, that betrayed him, knew the place: because \sc Jesus\sc* had often resorted thither together with his Disciples.
\v 3 Judas therefore having received the band of men, and of the chief Priests and Pharisees, ministers, cometh thither with lanterns and torches and weapons.
\v 4 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore knowing all things that should come upon him, went forth, and said to them: Whom seek ye?
\v 5 They answered him, \sc Jesus\sc* of Nazareth. \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: I am he. And Judas also that betrayed him, stood with them.
\v 6 As soon therefore as he said to them, I am he; they went backward, and fell to the ground.
\v 7 Again therefore he asked them: Whom seek ye? And they said: \sc Jesus\sc* of Nazareth.
\v 8 \sc Jesus\sc* answered, I have told you, that I am he. If therefore you seek me, let these go their ways.
\v 9 That the word might be fulfilled which he said, That of them whom thou hast given me, I have not lost any.
\v 10 Simon Peter therefore having a sword, drew it out; and smote the servant of the high Priest, & cut off his right ear. And the name of the servant was Malchus.
\v 11 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore said to Peter: Put up thy sword into the scabbard. The chalice which my Father hath given me, shall not I drink it?
\v 12 The band therefore and the Tribune & the ministers of the Jews apprehended \sc Jesus\sc*, and bound him:
\v 13 and they brought him to Annas first, for he was father in law to Caiphas, who was the high Priest of that year.
\v 14 And Caiphas was he that had given the counsel to the Jews, That it is expedient that one man die for the people.
\v 15 And Simon Peter followed \sc Jesus\sc*, and another Disciple. And that Disciple was known to the high Priest, and went in with \sc Jesus\sc* into the court of the high Priest.
\v 16 But Peter stood at the door without. The other Disciple therefore that was known to the high Priest, went forth, and spake to the portress, and brought in Peter.
\v 17 The wench therefore that was portress, saith to Peter: Art not thou also of this man's Disciples? He saith to her, I am not. \f + \fr 18:17 \ft It is all one for a man to deny Christ, and that he is a disciple of Christ, or a Catholic, or a Christian man, when he is demanded. Aug. tract. 113 in Io. for so Peter here denieth Christ, in denying himself to be his Disciple.\f*
\v 18 And the servants & ministers stood at a fire of coals, because it was cold, and warmed themselves. And with them was Peter also standing, and warming himself.
\v 19 The high Priest therefore asked \sc Jesus\sc* of his Disciples, and of his doctrine.
\v 20 \sc Jesus\sc* answered him: I have openly spoken to the world: I have always taught in the Synagogue, and in the temple whither all the Jews resort together: and in secret I have spoken nothing.
\v 21 Why askest thou me? ask them that have heard what I have spoken unto them: behold they know what things I have said.
\v 22 When he had said these things, one of the ministers standing by, gave \sc Jesus\sc* a blow, saying: Answerest thou the high Priest so?
\v 23 \sc Jesus\sc* answered him: If I have spoken ill, give testimony of evil: but if well, why strikest thou me?
\v 24 And Annas sent him bound to Caiphas the high priest.
\v 25 And Simon Peter was standing, and warming himself. They said therefore to him: Art not thou also of his Disciples: He denied and said: I am not.
\v 26 One of the servants of the high Priest saith to him, his cousin whose ear Peter did cut off: Did not I see thee in the garden with him?
\v 27 Again therefore Peter denied: and forthwith the cock crew.
\v 28 They therefore bring \sc Jesus\sc* from Caiphas into the Palace. And it was morning: and they went not in into the Palace, that they might not be contaminated, but that they might eat the Pasch. \f + \fr 18:28 \ft GOOD FRIDAY.\f*
\v 29 Pilate therefore went forth to them without, and said: What accusation bring you against this man?
\v 30 They answered and said to him: If he were not a malefactor, we would not have delivered him up to thee.
\v 31 Pilate therefore said to them: Take him you, and according to your law judge him. The Jews therefore said to him: It is not lawful for us to kill any man.
\v 32 That the word of \sc Jesus\sc* might be fulfilled which he said, signifying what death he should die.
\v 33 Pilate therefore went into the Palace again, and called \sc Jesus\sc*, and said to him: Art thou the King of the Jews?
\v 34 \sc Jesus\sc* answered: Sayest thou this of thyself, or have others told it thee of me?
\v 35 Pilate answered: Why, am I a Jew? Thy Nation, and the chief Priests have delivered thee up to me: what hast thou done? \f + \fr 18:35 \ft It pleased God, that Christ who was to die both for the Jews & the Gentiles, should be betrayed of the one, and put to death by the other.\f*
\v 36 \sc Jesus\sc* answered: My Kingdom is not of this world. If my Kingdom were of this world, my ministers verily would strive that I should not be delivered to the Jews. But now my Kingdom is not from hence.
\v 37 Pilate therefore said to him: Art thou a King then? \sc Jesus\sc* answered: Thou sayest, that I am a King. For this was I born, and for this came I into the world: that I should give testimony to the truth. Every one that is of the truth, heareth my voice.
\v 38 Pilate saith to him: What is truth? And when he had said this, he went forth again to the Jews, and saith to them: I find no cause in him.
\v 39 But you have a custom that I should release one to you in the Pasch: will you therefore that I release unto you the King of the Jews?
\v 40 They all therefore cried again, saying: Not him but Barabbas. And Barabbas was a thief.
\c 19
\p
\v 1 \sc Then\sc* therefore Pilate took \sc Jesus\sc*, and scourged him.
\v 2 And the soldiers platting a crown of thorns, put it upon his head: and they put about him a purple garment.
\v 3 And they came to him, and said: Hail King of the Jews; and they gave him blows.
\v 4 Pilate went forth again, and saith to them: Behold I bring him forth unto you, that you may know that I find no cause in him.
\v 5 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore went forth carrying the crown of thorns, and the purple vestiment. And he saith to them: Lo the man.
\v 6 When the chief Priests therefore and the ministers had seen him, they cried, saying: Crucify, crucify him. Pilate saith to them: Take him you, and crucify him. For I find no cause in him.
\v 7 The Jews answered him: We have a Law; and according to the Law he ought to die; because he hath made himself the Son of God.
\v 8 When Pilate therefore had heard this saying, he feared more.
\v 9 And he entered into the Palace again; and he saith to \sc Jesus\sc*: Whence art thou? But \sc Jesus\sc* gave him no answer.
\v 10 Pilate therefore saith to him: Speakest thou not to me? knowest thou not that I have power to crucify thee, and I have power to release thee?
\v 11 \sc Jesus\sc* answered: Thou shouldest not have any power against me, unless it were given thee from above. Therefore he that hath betrayed me to thee, hath the greater sin.
\v 12 From thence forth Pilate sought to release him. But the Jews cried, saying: If thou release this man, thou art not Cæsar's friend. Every one that maketh himself a king, speaketh against Cæsar.
\v 13 But Pilate when he had heard these words, brought forth \sc Jesus\sc*: and he sat in the judgement seat, in the place that is called Lithostrotos, and in Hebrew Gabbatha.
\v 14 And it was the Parasceve of Pasch, about the sixth hour, and he saith to the Jews: Lo your King. \f + \fr 19:14 \ft He meaneth midday, counting from sun rising. For so doth the Scripture count the hours of the day. Mat. 20. Mar. 15. Luc. 23. Io. 4. Act. 3. & 10.\f*
\v 15 But they cried: Away, away with him, crucify him. Pilate saith to them: Shall I crucify your King? The chief Priests answered: We have no King, but Cæsar.
\v 16 Then therefore he delivered him unto them for to be crucified. And they took \sc Jesus\sc*, and led him forth.
\v 17 And bearing his own cross he went forth into that which is called the place of Calvary, in Hebrew Golgotha.
\v 18 Where they crucified him, and with him two others, on the one side & on the other, and in the midst \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 19 And Pilate wrote a title also: and he put it upon the cross. And it was written, \sc Jesus of Nazareth The King of The Jews\sc*.
\v 20 This title therefore many of the Jews did read: because the place where \sc Jesus\sc* was crucified, was nigh to the city: and it was written in Hebrew, in Greek, and in Latin. \f + \fr 19:20 \ft These three tongues being for other causes most famous before in all the world, are now also dedicated to God in the triumphant title of the Cross of Christ, and in them the Holy Scriptures are more conveniently written, taught, & preserved.\f*
\v 21 The chief Priests therefore of the Jews said to Pilate: Write not, The King of the Jews; but that he said, I am King of the Jews.
\v 22 Pilate answered: That which I have written, I have written.
\v 23 The soldiers therefore when they had crucified him, took his garments (and they made four parts, to every soldier a part) & his coat. And his coat was without seam, wrought from the top throughout. \f + \fr 19:23 \ft This coat without seam is a figure of the unity of the church. Cypr. de unit. Ec. And Euthymius and other write that our Lady made it.\f*
\v 24 They said therefore one to another: Let us not cut it, but let us cast lots for it whose it shall be. That the scripture might be fulfilled saying: \add They have parted my garments among them: and upon my vesture they have cast lots.\add* And the soldiers did these things.
\v 25 And there stood beside the cross of \sc Jesus\sc*, his mother, and his mother's sister, Mary of Cleophas, and Mary Magdalene. \f + \fr 19:25 \ft The Gospel in a votive Mass of our B. Lady between Easter & Whitsunday.\f* \f + \fr 19:25 \ft The great love, faith, courage, compassion, and sorrows, that our Lady had: who forsook not the Cross and her Son, when so many were fled from him, and his chief Apostles denied him.\f*
\v 26 When \sc Jesus\sc* therefore had seen his mother and the Disciple standing whom he loved, he saith to his mother: Woman, behold thy son.
\v 27 After that, he saith to the Disciple: Behold thy mother. And from that hour the Disciple took her to his own.
\v 28 Afterward \sc Jesus\sc* knowing that all things were now consummate, that the scripture might be fulfilled, he saith, I thirst. \f + \fr 19:28 \ft b The Gospel in a votive Mass of the Passion.\f*
\v 29 Avessel therefore stood there full of vinegar. And they putting a sponge full of vinegar about hyssop, offered it to his mouth.
\v 30 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore when he had taken the vinegar, said: It is consummate. And bowing his head, he gave up the ghost.
\v 31 The Jews therefore (because it was the Parasceve) that the bodies might not remain upon the cross on the Sabboth (for that was a great Sabboth day) they desired Pilate that their legs might be broken, and they might be taken away.
\v 32 The soldiers therefore came: and of the first indeed they brake the legs, and of the other that was crucified with him.
\v 33 But after they were come to \sc Jesus\sc*, when they saw that he was dead, they did not break his legs,
\v 34 but one of the soldiers with a spear opened his side, & incontinent there came forth blood and water.
\v 35 And he that saw it, hath given testimony: and his testimony is true. And he knoweth that he saith true, that you also may believe.
\v 36 For these things were done that the scripture might be fulfilled: \add You shall not break a bone of him.\add*
\v 37 And again another scripture saith: \add They shall look on him whom they pierced.\add*
\v 38 And after these things Joseph of Arimathæa (because he was a Disciple of \sc Jesus\sc*, but secret for fear of the Jews) desired Pilate that he might take away the body of \sc Jesus\sc*. And Pilate permitted. He came therefore, & took away the body of \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 39 Nicodemus also came, he that at the first came to \sc Jesus\sc* by night, bringing a mixture of myrrh and aloes, about an hundred pounds.
\v 40 They took therefore the body of \sc Jesus\sc*, and bound it in linen cloths with the spices, as the manner is with the Jews to bury.
\v 41 And there was in the place where he was crucified, a garden: and in the garden a new monument, wherein no man yet had been laid.
\v 42 There therefore because of the Parasceve of the Jews, they laid \sc Jesus\sc*, because the monument was hard by.
\c 20
\p
\v 1 \sc And\sc* the first of the Sabboth, Mary Magdalene cometh early, when it was yet dark, unto the monument: and she saw the stone taken away from the monument. \f + \fr 20:1 \ft The Gospel upon Saturday in Easter week.\f* \f + \fr 20:1 \ft That is, the first day of the week, as some interpret it, taking Sabboth (as sometime it is) for a week. This is our Sunday, called Dies Dominica, because of our Lord's resurrection. See the marg. annot. Luc. 24, 1.\f*
\v 2 She ran therefore and cometh to Simon Peter, and to the other Disciple whom \sc Jesus\sc* loved, and saith to them: They have taken our Lord out of the monument, and we know not where they have laid him.
\v 3 Peter therefore went forth and that other Disciple, and they came to the monument.
\v 4 And both ran together, and that other Disciple did out-run Peter, and came first to the monument.
\v 5 And when he had stooped down, he saw the linen cloths lying: but yet he went not in.
\v 6 Simon Peter therefore cometh, following him, and went into the monument and saw the linen cloths lying,
\v 7 and the napkin that had been upon his head, not lying with the linen cloths, but apart, wrapped up into one place.
\v 8 Then therefore went in that other Disciple also which came first to the monument: and he saw, and believed.
\v 9 For as yet they knew not the scripture, that he should rise again from the dead.
\v 10 The Disciples therefore departed again to themselves.
\v 11 But Mary stood at the monument without, weeping. Therefore as she was weeping, she stooped down, & looked into the monument: \f + \fr 20:11 \ft b The Gospel upon Thursday in Easter week.\f* \f + \fr 20:11 \ft The Sepulchres of Martyrs (saith S. Hierom ep. 17. ) we do honour every-where, & putting their holy ashes to our eyes, if we may, we touch it also with our mouth: and be there some that think the monument wherein our Lord was laid, is to be neglected: where the Devil and his Angels, as often as they are cast out of the possessed before the said monument, tremble and roar as if they stood before the judgement seat of Christ?\f*
\v 12 and she saw two Angels in white, sitting, one at the head, and one at the feet, where the body of \sc Jesus\sc* had been laid.
\v 13 They say to her: Woman, why weepest thou? She saith to them: Because they have taken away my Lord, and I know not where they have put him.
\v 14 When she had said thus, she turned backward, and saw \sc Jesus\sc* standing; and she knew not that it is \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 15 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to her: Woman, why weepest thou? whom seekest thou? She thinking that it was the gardener, saith to him: Sir, if thou hast carried him away, tell me where thou hast laid him; and I will take him away.
\v 16 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to her: Mary. She turning saith to him: Rabboni (which is to say, Master.)
\v 17 \sc Jesus\sc* said to her: Do not touch me, for I am not yet ascended to my Father: but go to my Brethren, and say to them, I ascend to my Father and your Father, my God and your God.
\v 18 Mary Magdalene cometh and telleth the Disciples, That I have seen our Lord, and thus he said unto me.
\v 19 Therefore when it was late that day, the first of the Sabboths, and the doors were shut, where the Disciples were gathered together for fear of the Jews, \sc Jesus\sc* came and stood in the midst, and saith to them: Peace be to you. \f + \fr 20:19 \ft The Gospel upon Dominica in albis or Low Sunday, And for peace.\f*
\v 20 And when he had said this, he shewed them his hands and side. The Disciples therefore were glad when they saw our Lord.
\v 21 He said therefore to them again: Peace be to you. As my Father hath sent me, I also do send you. \f + \fr 20:21 \ft Though he gave them his peace hard before, yet now entering to a new divine action, to prepare their hearts to grace and attention, he blesseth them again.\f*
\v 22 When he had said this: he breathed upon them; and he said to them: Receive ye the Holy Ghost:
\v 23 \sc Whose Sins You Shall Forgive, They Are Forgiven Them: And Whose You Shall Retain, They Are Retained\sc*.
\v 24 But Thomas one of the Twelve, who is called Didymus, was not with them when \sc Jesus\sc* came. \f + \fr 20:24 \ft The Gospel upon S. Thomas the Apostle's day, Decemb. 21.\f*
\v 25 The other Disciples therefore said to him: We have seen our Lord. But he said to them: unless I see in his hands the print of the nails, and put my finger into the place of the nails, and put my hand into his side: I will not believe.
\v 26 And after eight days, again his Disciples were within; and Thomas with them. \sc Jesus\sc* cometh the doors being shut, and stood in the midst, and said: Peace be to you. \f + \fr 20:26 \ft LOW SUNDAY.\f* \f + \fr 20:26 \ft See the annotation on the 19. verse of this Chapter.\f*
\v 27 Then he saith to Thomas: Put in thy finger hither, and see my hands, and bring hither thy hand, and put it into my side; & be not incredulous but faithful.
\v 28 Thomas answered, & said to him: My Lord, & my God.
\v 29 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: Because thou hast seen me, Thomas, thou hast believed: Blessed are they that have not seen & have believed. \f + \fr 20:29 \ft They are more happy that believe without sensible argument or sight, than such as be induced by sense or reason to believe.\f*
\v 30 Many other signs also did \sc Jesus\sc* in the sight of his Disciples, which are not written in this Book.
\v 31 And these are written, that you may believe that \sc Jesus\sc* is \sc Christ\sc* the Son of God: and that believing, you may have life in his name.
\c 21
\p
\v 1 \sc After Jesus\sc* manifested himself again to the Disciples at the sea of Tiberias. And he manifested thus. \f + \fr 21:1 \ft The Gospel on Wednesday in Easter week.\f*
\v 2 There were together Simon Peter, and Thomas who is called Didymus, and Nathanael which was of Cana in Galilee, & the sons of Zebedee, and two others of his Disciples.
\v 3 Simon Peter saith to them: I go to fish. They say to him: We also come with thee. And they went forth and got up into the boat: and that night they took nothing.
\v 4 But when morning was now come, \sc Jesus\sc* stood on the shore: yet the Disciples knew not that it was \sc Jesus\sc*.
\v 5 \sc Jesus\sc* therefore saith to them: Children, have you any meat? They answered him, No.
\v 6 He saith to them: Cast the net on the right side of the boat; and you shall find. They therefore did cast it: and now they were not able to draw it for the multitude of fishes.
\v 7 That Disciples therefore whom \sc Jesus\sc* loved, saith to Peter: It is our Lord. Simon Peter when he had heard that it is our Lord, girded his coat unto him (for he was naked) & cast himself into the sea. \f + \fr 21:7 \ft See in S. Augustine tract. 122. in Io. the great mystery hereof concerning the CHURCH, and in S. Gregory hom. 24. in Evang. and S. Bernard li. 2. c. 8 de consid. Peter's PRIMACY here mystically signified.\f*
\v 8 But the other Disciples came in the boat (for they were not far from the land, but as it were two hundred cubits) drawing the net of fishes.
\v 9 Therefore after they came down to land, they saw hot coals lying, and fish laid thereon, and bread.
\v 10 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: Bring hither of the fishes that you took now.
\v 11 Simon Peter went up, and drew the net to the land, full of great fishes, an hundred fifty three. And although they were so many the net was not broken.
\v 12 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to them: Come, dine. And none of them that sat at meat, durst ask him: Who art thou? knowing that it is our Lord. \f + \fr 21:12 \ft the disciples,\f*
\v 13 And \sc Jesus\sc* cometh & taketh the bread and giveth them, & the fish in like manner.
\v 14 This now the third time \sc Jesus\sc* was manifested to his Disciples, after he was risen from the dead. \f + \fr 21:14 \ft Not the third apparition, but the third day of his apparitions: for he appeared in the very day of his Resurrection often, again upon Low Sunday, then this third time, And S. Mark saying, last he appeared, c. 16, 14: meaneth his last apparition the first day.\f*
\v 15 Therefore when they had dined, \sc Jesus\sc* saith to Simon Peter: Simon of John, lovest thou me more than these? He saith to him: Yea Lord; thou knowest that I love thee. He saith to him: \sc Feed my Lambs\sc*. \f + \fr 21:15 \ft The Gospel on the eve of SS. Peter and Paul.\f*
\v 16 He saith to him again: Simon of John, lovest thou me? He saith to him: Yea Lord, thou knowest that I love thee. He saith to him: \sc Feed my Lambs\sc*. \f + \fr 21:16 \ft c ποίμαινε feed & rule.\f*
\v 17 He saith to him the third time: Simon of John, lovest thou me? Peter was stroken sad because he said unto him the third time, Lovest thou me? And he said to him: Lord, thou knowest all things: thou knowest that I love thee. He said to him: \sc Feed my Sheep\sc*.
\v 18 Amen, amen I say to thee, when thou wast younger, thou didst gird thyself, and didst walk where thou wouldest. But when thou shalt be old thou shalt stretch forth thy hands, and another shall gird thee, and lead thee whither thou wilt not.
\v 19 And this he said, signifying by what death he should glorify God. And when he had said this, he saith to him: Follow me. \f + \fr 21:19 \ft b The Gospel upon S. John the Evangelist's day in Christmas\f*
\v 20 Peter turning, saw that Disciple whom \sc Jesus\sc* loved, following, who also leaned at the supper upon his breast, and said, Lord who is he that shall betray thee?
\v 21 Him therefore when Peter had seen, he saith to \sc Jesus\sc*: Lord, and this man what?
\v 22 \sc Jesus\sc* saith to him: So I will have him to remain till I come, what to thee? follow thou me. \f + \fr 21:22 \ft c So readeth S. Ambrose in Ps. 45. & ser. 20 in Ps. 118. S. Aug. tract. 124 in Io. & most ancient copies and service books extant in Latin. Others read, If I will: others, If so I will, &c.\f*
\v 23 This saying therefore went abroad among the brethren, that that Disciple dieth not. And \sc Jesus\sc* did not say to him, he dieth not; but, So I will have him to remain till I come, what to thee?
\v 24 This is that Disciple which giveth testimony of these things, and hath written these things: and we know that his testimony is true.
\v 25 But there are many other things also which \sc Jesus\sc* did: which if they were written in particular, neither the world it-self I think were able to contain those books that should be written. \f + \fr 21:25 \ft Beza in hunc locum.\f* \f + \fr 21:25 \ft How few things are written of Christ's acts & doctrine in comparison of that which he did and spake: and yet the Heretics will needs have all in Scripture, trusting not the Apostle's own preaching, or report of any thing that our Master did or said, if it be not written.\f*
